dict.string: Occurs in coastal waters of New Zealand, Chatham Islands and south to the Snares Islands. Also found in southern Australia.
Has a small rounded head and downturned mouth. Average size of 30 to 50 cm but can grow up to 70 cm.
Herbivorous, feeds on red coralline turf.
Solitary fish, lives in water to about 20 m. Occurs on reefs, near caves and crevices.
Olive green or brown marbled with white. Swims with winding motion.
It is common around the northern half of the North Island of New Zealand. Found in tropical and temperate waters of the Southern Hemisphere, it is also common in the northern Pacific.

Has a long and streamlined body. It is greenish-blue or purplish-blue above and silvery-white below. The top half and bottom half are clearly separated by a yellow band. The tail, pectoral and pelvic fins are yellow. It has an average size of 60 cm to 1.2 m but can grow up to 1.8 m.

Inquisitive, it will investigate a snorkeler, diver and even a boat. It can be solitary or found in large schools. Spawns in spring-summer. Juveniles are pelagic and grow up to 50 cm in the first two years. They mature at about 5 years old.
Feeds on small school-fishes and frequently seen pursuing them right into shallow water. Small fishes often leap from the water in frantic endeavours to evade kingfish.
It is more abundant in coastal waters (harbours, bays, and reefs) during the warmer months but can still be found deeper in cooler months of the year.
Juveniles and adult fish have a yellow band on the flank from the snout to the tail.
Common in coastal waters of New Zealand and southern Australia.

A small schooling fish with long pectoral fins and a row of large bony scales along the side of its tail. The lateral line drops sharply midway down the body. Has a black spot on its gill cover. Average size is 20 to 30 cm but can grow up to 55 cm.
Spawns in spring and summer. Lives up to 28 years.
Feeds on plankton and small pelagic (mid water) fishes.
Found in mid water all along the coast. More abundant in summer than winter.
Yellow-green above, white below and yellow tail.
Common in coastal waters of northern New Zealand.
The lips are big and fleshy. The lower rays of the pectoral fins are a little longer and more fleshy than the upper ones. Average size of 35 to 45 cm but can grow up to 70 cm.
Spawns between March and May. Juveniles are found in rock pools and shallow waters between September and November. Matures after about 2 years and lives up to 60 years old.
Feeds on small benthic (sea floor) crustaceans and sea stars.
Mostly encountered in northern shallow waters of New Zealand. This fish is territorial and tends to live in the same area year round.
Common in shallow coastal waters of northeastern New Zealand and southern Australia.

The pectoral fins are well developed and are used to grip onto the bottom where it mostly stays. Inquisitive, it will come very close to snorkelers. Average size of 25 to 30 cm but can grow up to 35cm.
Spawning occurs in winter. Juveniles are always found in shallow surgy waters.
Feeds on a wide range of benthic (sea floor) invertebrates and small fishes.
It is mostly encountered in northern shallow waters of New Zealand. The fish is territorial and tends to live in the same area year round.
Marbled olive-brown with dense white spots.
Common all around New Zealand and in southeastern Australia.

The lips are golden and has golden patches on the face. It lives in schools in shallow surgy waters. Shy, it will often swim as fast as possible from snorkelers. Average size of 30 to 40 cm but can grow up to 45 cm.
Spawns in spring and summer. Matures at 5 years old and lives up to 10 years.
Juveniles feed on plankton, detritus and parasites of other fishes while adults mostly feed on seaweed.
Found in estuaries and coastal reefs shallower than 10 m.
Silvery fish with 9 to 12 fine vertical black bands.
Common in northeastern New Zealand and southeastern Australia.

Olive green above, silver below, has grey markings on its face. Tail and fins are black. This schooling fish is very wary and will swim away from snorkelers. Average size of 30 to 50 cm but can grow up to 75 cm.
Juveniles are more camouflaged, they are olive green with white spots. Juveniles can be seen in very shallow waters from January to April.
Feeds on large brown seaweed, green and red encrusting algae.
Always found in exposed reef areas.
Chubby silver body with black tail.
Common all around New Zealand and in southeastern Australia.
Lives in large schools. Very inquisitive, will follow snorkelers around. Can grow up to 35 cm.
Spawns in winter. Juveniles can be seen hiding in rock crevices between July and October.
Schools in midwater on shallow reefs.
Diamond shaped and laterally compressed silver-grey body.
Lives in large schools. Very inquisitive and will follow snorkelers around. Average size of 25 to 35 cm but can grow up to 40 cm.
Spawns in winter. Juveniles can be seen on reefs between October and January.
Schools at the surface and in midwater on shallow reefs.
Laterally compressed, electric blue oval body. Juveniles are a pale blue but have a yellow anal fin.
Common in northeastern New Zealand, found around Norfolk Island and eastern Australia.

Juveniles are white with a yellow stripe from the snout to the tail where it ends in a black dot. Females have a cream coloured body and two darker patches on either side of the upper body. Males have a purple body with a saddle of white, brown and yellow stripes. Females grow up to 35 cm, males have an average size of 35 to 50 cm.
All juveniles are females, only the dominant female of a group of up to 20 will change into a male. Spawning occurs between December and March.
Feeds on a variety of benthic (sea floor) invertebrates, and will pick parasites from the bodies of other fish.
Prefers sandy areas bordering reefs. Sleeps at night buried under a thin layer of sand.
Undergoes sex reversal. The larger, dominant female within each school can change sex when the male dies or is removed.
Commonly found around New Zealand but absent from the Three Kings and Snares Islands.

Juveniles and females are yellowish brown with a black area in the middle of the body. Males are greyish brown with blue dots, golden markings on the head only and a series of black spots under the dorsal fin.
Spawning season is between July and December. Juveniles become mature in their first or second year. Changes from female to male between 3 and 4 years of age. Can live up to 7 years.
Has a wide diet, feeds on small crustaceans, worms, seashells and sea stars.
Can be found anywhere from estuaries to shallow reefs. Males are found deeper than females. At night they sleep in a mucus coating that they secrete.
Is not shy and will interact with a snorkeler. Average size of 15 to 25 cm but can grow up to 30 cm.
Found around New Zealand but more common around the North Island. It also occurs in eastern Australia.

Can rapidly change colour to mimic its surroundings. Most individuals have a darker brown line stretching from the eye to the tail. Breeding males have blue lines on the head and blue dots over the rest of the body. It has an average size of 15 to 30 cm but can grow up to 45 cm.
Spawning season is between October and January. This is when the beautifully coloured males fight amongst each other for territory and females.
Uses its highly sensitive barbels to detect seashells, worms and crustaceans that live in bottom sediments.
Lives in schools of 5 to 15 individuals. Prefers sandy areas bordering reefs.
Lives on the bottom. Sandy to red coloured body. Pair of barbels (fleshy whiskers) under the chin.
Found around New Zealand from very shallow reefs to 20 m depth.
Has a slender body with a small mouth which is armed with a strong sharp beak. Average size of 35 to 45 cm but can grow up to 70 cm.

The spawning season starts in July and finishes in February. Males are territorial during the breeding season. All begin life as female but change into males once they reach 35 to 40 cm after 4 to 5 years. Males can live up to 10 years old.
Herbivorous, feeds only on large brown seaweeds. Bites off bits of kelp leaf leaving circular holes.

Juveniles and females are dark yellow green with a silver line from the snout to the tail, males are dark greenish blue with a lighter coloured band from snout to tail; with blue lines and dots on the head and body.
Found around New Zealand in intertidal rock pools and estuaries.
The dorsal fin is elongate and spikey, and the fish uses it to brace itself in crevices or under rocks. Average size of 10 to 20 cm but can grow up to 30 cm.
Eggs are laid in winter and spring. The male will guard the nest until the eggs hatch after about 10 days. Can live up to 9 years.
It hides in cracks or under boulders on rocky, sandy or muddy shores. If disturbed will rapidly escape to find shelter under another rock.
Small, brown to olive green body and a white stripe on the head. The long dorsal fin starts just behind the head and finishes at the base of the tail.
Found around New Zealand and southern Australia.

Young snapper have 4 or 5 darker vertical bands on the body and electric blue spots. Adults lose the bands and the spots may fade, and bigger fish can also develop a hump on the head. They have powerful jaws and canine teeth. Average size of 30 to 50 cm but can grow up to 100 cm.

During the early summer months, most of the mature snapper will gather off shore to spawn in large aggregations. All snapper are females until about three years old, then about half of them will turn male. Can live to at least 63 years of age.
Carnivorous and opportunistic. Its wide diet consists of crustaceans, seashells, other fishes, worms and echinoderms.
Anyone fishing off the shore or snorkeling on a sandy bottom can encounter juvenile snapper. Found anywhere between shallow estuaries to 200 m depth.
Pink with small blue dots above and silver below; older fish are dark brown. Snapper is the best known fish in New Zealand.
Found all around New Zealand and in Australia. Introduced to Australia from New Zealand.

Highly variable mottled colour pattern of green, yellow, brown or red; the belly is a cream colour. The tip of the first two dorsal fins is electric blue. Has yellow eyes. Average size of 8 to 10 cm but can grow up to 20 cm.
Spawns between May and November. Females lay up to 4 batches of eggs on rock walls. The male guards the nests until the eggs hatch. Males grow faster and bigger than females.
Carnivorous, feeds on small benthic (sea floor) invertebrates.
Found on rocky reefs from shallow waters to about 10 m depth
Small fish with yellow eyes and three dorsal fins. The tip of the first two fins is electric blue. It always rests on the bottom.
Found all around New Zealand and in Australia. Introduced to Australia from New Zealand.
Colour varies from white to orangy-brown. A black stripe starts above the eye and finishes at the base of the tail. Second and third dorsal fins are red. Can grow up to 8 cm.
Spawns between June and January. Females lay eggs under boulders or within coralline algae. Males guard the nest for 20 days, until the eggs hatch.
Carnivorous, feeds on small invertebrates and parasites from larger fishes.
Found on rocky reefs from shallow waters to about 5 m depth
Small fish with three dorsal fins. Second and third dorsal fins are red. It always rests on the bottom.
Highly variable mottled colour pattern of green, grey, brown, and beige. Steep forehead. Can grow up to 7 cm.
Spawns in winter-spring. Eggs are laid in crevices in the upper rocky shore. Exposed at low tide, the nests are guarded by the male at high tide.
Feeds on small encrusting invertebrates such as chitons and barnacles.
Found in rock pools and crevices.
Small fish with three dorsal fins. It always rests on the bottom.
Found around New Zealand in shallow coastal sandy and muddy shores and in estuaries. Also found in eastern Australia.

Brown above, pale yellow below, almost invisible on muddy or sandy bottoms where it can partially bury itself. The eyes are both found on the right side of the body and it lies on its left side. Average size of 25 to 35 cm but can grow up to 45 cm.

Spawns offshore. Each larva starts life with an eye on each side of its head. During transformation into a juvenile, the left eye migrates to the right side of the head, which becomes the upper side of the fish when it settles on the bottom. Lives up to 4 years.
Carnivorous, preys on crustaceans, worms and seashells.
Found in estuaries, brackish water, and on muddy or sandy bottoms of shallow coastal waters.
Diamond-shaped, flattened fish. Can change colour within seconds to blend in with its the environment.
Found in northern New Zealand and southern Australia.

Usually mottled pink, red, white and yellow but can also change colour to match its environment. It rests on the bottom, immobile; a snorkeler can get as close as a few centimetres away. Average size of 15 to 20 cm but can grow up to 60 cm.
Has a venomous dorsal fin. Fertilises its eggs internally and gives birth to free living young.
Hunts at the night; feeds on small fishes, crabs, shrimps, and small octopus. During the day if unsuspected prey swims too close to its mouth it will be swallowed whole.
Can be seen on reefs, in the open or in caves and under boulders.
Well camouflaged, it looks like a rock covered by encrusting red algae. Head and mouth large compared to the rest of its body.
Found around New Zealand and southeastern Australia.

A small fish with a tube-like mouth. Its body is yellowish brown with darker spots over the head and body. It can grow up to 34 cm high. The body is narrow and strongly cross ridged on the sides. The prehensile tail is used for attachment to seaweeds. Its excellent camouflage makes it hard to see.
Can breed all year round. The male keeps the eggs in his large ventral pouch until they hatch. A single male can 'give birth' to up to 721 young. Believed to live for 4 to 5 years.
Attaches to seaweeds where it waits for tiny crustacean prey which are then sucked into its tubular mouth.
Found in seaweed-covered rocks in harbours, bays and reefs throughout New Zealand.
Horse-like head and long, prehensile tail. The body is covered in bony rings and does not have scales.

Has big round black eyes. The dorsal and anal fins are very close to the tail. Average size of 25 to 35 cm but can grow up to 60 cm. If threatened, can inflate itself with water, turning into a spiky balloon to discourage any potential predator.
For some of the close relatives of the porcupinefish it has been reported that organs, such as the liver, contain tetrodotoxin and are extremely poisonous to eat.
Carnivorous, uses the powerful jaws to crush seashells, urchins and crabs.
Single fish can be seen over shallow reefs. Docile, it can be approached by snorkelers.
Body covered with spines, grey above, white below, yellow markings on the sides.
Found around New Zealand and eastern Australia.

The skin is very rough. The dorsal spine can be raised if the fish is threatened while feeding or when it is being aggressive towards a competitor. Average size of 20 to 30 cm but can grow up to 35 cm.

Spawning occurs in August. The eggs are laid on the bottom and left unguarded. Juveniles settle during the summer months and hide in kelp. Young take up to two years to reach adult size. Can live up to 7 years.
Feeds on small benthic (sea floor) invertebrates, sponges, jellyfish and salps.
Found on reefs and sandy areas.
Narrow diamond-shaped brown body with a small mouth. Has a hard dorsal spine. Very social, it will investigate snorkelers and swimmers, and may even bite them.
Found all around New Zealand but more abundant in the north. This fish is also found around Europe, Africa, Southeast Asia, Australia and Japan.
The body is light grey or brown with dark greenish-brown wavy stripes. It is well camouflaged and hard to see underwater. Average size of 30 to 45 cm but can grow up to 60 cm.
Spawning occurs between December and April. Females grow bigger than males and live up to 9 years old. Males live for up to 7 years.
Hunts for a variety of small to medium sized reef fishes. Once a few centimetres away from its prey, the John Dory will shoot out its telescopic mouth and swallow the prey whole.
Found mostly in the waters of the North Island and upper South Island. Usually solitary, can be seen in greater numbers near reefs during summer. Glides just above sandy or rocky bottoms.
Extremely thin bodied, with a large, central, black spot surrounded by a silvery white margin. Otherwise camouflaged by a wavy colour pattern. Has a very tall dorsal fin.
Found around New Zealand, also occurs in other temperate waters of the Pacific and Atlantic Oceans.
As indicated by its name, it is a beautiful bronze colour with a cream belly. The upper part of the tail is a lot longer than the lower part.
The females have a gestation period of about a year and can give birth to up to 24 pups.
Feeds on a wide variety of fishes and squid.
This shark is encountered mostly by spear fisherman in shallow waters of the North Island of New Zealand.
Rarely seen unless attracted by dying or bleeding fishes, though often seen by spear fishers. Can measure up to 3 m.
Occurs in the northeastern and southwestern Atlantic Ocean, northeastern and southeastern Pacific Ocean, and around South Africa, South Australia and New Zealand.

Sharply pointed nose, slender, grey above and white below. The second dorsal fin is the same size as the anal fin. Has a long lobe to the end of the tail. Average size of 1.2 to 1.5 m but can grow up to 2 m.
Can live up to 60 years. Larger females will produce litters of up to 52 pups.
It is an opportunistic feeder and preys on bony fish and squid.

Large harbours, like the west coast's Manukau and Kaipara harbours, are important nursing ground for this species. It forms schools segregated by sex and size. Is migratory and can cover long distances; individuals have been known to cross the Tasman Sea to Australia.
Medium-sized shark which is the most common shark in New Zealand waters. It is commercially harvested for its flesh, fins and liver oil. It has a sail-like piece of skin on the upper tail.
Found all around New Zealand and Norfolk Island but not the Chatham and subantarctic islands.
Greyish brown, with rows of white spots. It has an asymmetrical tail with the upper lobe much larger than the lower lobe. Has fairly large eyes. Average size of 70 cm to 1 m but can grow up to 1.4 m.
A rather fast growing shark which lives to about 15 years old. The larger females, after a gestation period of 11 months, can give birth to up to 22 pups.
Feeds on benthic (sea floor) crustaceans, especially crabs.

During the summer months, it forms large schools close to shore down to 200 m depth. Stays deeper during winter. Migrates up and down New Zealand waters all year round. Often spotted sitting on sandy bottoms.
This small, abundant but harmless shark is commercially harvested and sold as "lemon fish" in fish and chips shops around New Zealand.
Occurs in tropical and temperate waters of the Pacific, Indian and Atlantic Oceans.

A large heavy-bodied shark that can measure up to 6 m. The eyes are round and very black. Countershaded in grey above and white below. The large triangular teeth can measure up to 7.5 cm long. Will sometimes jump clear out of the water when chasing prey.
Warm-blooded, gives birth to between 2 and 10 pups after 12 months gestation. Breeds every 2 to 3 years.

Young sharks feed on small fish while adults feed on larger prey such as whales, seals, or other sharks. In New Zealand it has been responsible for one fatal attack, but in reality humans are not the preferred prey of this shark.

Has one of the largest habitat ranges of any species, from shallow coastal to pelagic waters, it can swim down to depths of 1,200 m. It is highly migratory and will "follow" food. It can be found around seal colonies off the Chatham Islands and Stewart Island all year round, but the chances of encounter are highest from October to March.
Has a heavy upper body. The tail is nearly symmetrical, with the lower part of the tail almost as large as the upper part. The under side of the pectoral fins are black at the tips.
Found mostly north of Cook Strait in New Zealand waters. Also occurs in South Africa and southern Australia.
Dark grey black above, white underneath. It has multiple sharp thorns on the head, back and tail. Can reach 1.8 m width, with a total length up to 4 m, and weight up to 210 kg.
The biology and behaviour of this species is poorly known.
Feeds on small fishes and benthic (sea floor) invertebrates.
Commonly seen in harbours, estuaries, and bays. Can be encountered around reefs throughout New Zealand but is more abundant around the North Island.
A large ray without a dorsal fin. Dark in colour, its tail is longer than its body. Has a poisonous, barbed spine.
Commonly found around the North Island of New Zealand. Also occurs in southern Africa and southern Australia.

Greyish to black above and white underneath, it has a row of white pores on the wings. Apart from its large size it is easily recognised by rows of spines on the tail and the hard bony barb, up to 28 cm long, halfway down the tail. Can reach 2.1 m width, has a total length up to 4.3 m, and weighs up to 350 kg.
They are seen close to shore in autumn and summer. Viviparous, they give birth to 6 to 10 independent pups.
Feeds on small fish and benthic (sea floor) invertebrates.

Commonly seen in harbours, estuaries, and bays. Can be encountered around reefs throughout New Zealand but is more abundant around the North Island. Large aggregations have been noticed in some areas, such as the Poor Knights Islands.

Our largest stingray species. It is without a dorsal fin. Dark in colour, armed with a poisonous barb and with many small spikes on a short tail. Is a curious, gentle giant but defends itself if harassed. Can bring its tail right around and above its back to use the barb in defence.
Common in coastal waters of the North Island but less abundant south of Cook Strait.

Has a thick body with a bluntly rounded snout. The colour varies from dirty greenish-grey to almost black. It is harmless except for a hard bony spine on the smooth tail. Average size of 50 cm to 1 m but can grow up to 2 m.
Viviparous, it gives birth to free swimming pups. During summer months females will have litters of about 6 young.
Feeds on seashells and crabs, which it crushes with its powerful jaws.
Abundant over sandy and muddy habitats where it feeds, can be observed resting on sandy patches amongst reef areas.
A large ray without a dorsal fin. The end of the fins are pointed. Has light greyish blue markings above. It is a powerful swimmer and fights hard if caught on a fishing line.
Common in coastal waters of New Zealand.
The head is broad and flattened. The rest of the body is narrow. Underneath between the pectoral fins, it has a sucking disk which is uses to stick to rock or seaweed. Can grow up to 7 cm.
Breeding occurs in spring and summer. It is short lived and reaches maturity rapidly. Will move rapidly to another urchin or rock shelter if disturbed.
Feeds on sea urchin tube feet and small crustaceans.
Juveniles are found living under sea urchins. Adults can be seen in rock pools at low tide or in shallow rocky areas hiding under rocks, in crevices or sea weed.
A small fish with reddish head which slowly blends into greyish-white at the tail. The head has white lines, the eyes are blue.
Found around New Zealand, but most abundant in the south.

Has a single long dorsal fin. Juveniles up to 10 cm are white with a dark stripe on the midline of the back and a stripe just below on either side. Fish between 10-25 cm are browner and the stripes are not as marked, while mature fish over 25 cm are mostly countershaded blue above and white below.

Spawns during late winter and spring. Eggs and larvae float in the water column for about five days for each life stage (10 days total), before the larvae settle to the sea floor. In Northland this species is sexually mature at 10-19 cm and 2 years of age, in the Marlborough Sounds it matures between 21-26 cm and 3-6 years, while in Southland it is between 26-28 cm and 4-5 years. The maximum recorded age is 32 years.
Carnivorous, feeds mainly on small fishes and crabs, which it stalks and swallows whole.
Benthic (sea-floor) dwelling, on or near rocky reefs to a depth of 150m.
Has 3 age-related colour phases, with only the adult phase as blue. Supports a commercial fishery, mainly off Southland and Chatham Islands.
Found all around New Zealand and southern Australia.
Arm count can be anywhere between 7 and 14. The orange tube feet end in a suction-cup-like appendage. Grows up to 35 cm across.
Spawning is between November and March. The eggs and sperm are released in the water column, where they fertilise.
Carnivorous, feeds on a wide variety of shellfish.
Can be found at low tide and in shallow waters in sheltered harbours and bays.
Usually has 11 arms. Brown body with darker brown bands. Spiky all over.
Found up and down the west coast of New Zealand
A beautifully coloured sea star which usually has 11 arms. The tube feet end in a suction-cup-like appendage. The upper side is covered by granules. Grows up to 25 cm across.
It is very tough and rarely loses arms.
Found on exposed rocky shores of the west coasts of New Zealand.
Orange, pink or purple. The arms are shorter than the diameter of the central disc.
Found in northeastern New Zealand, the Pacific and Indian Oceans.
Beige, often with dark brown patches on the central disc. The tube feet are pointed. It has 5 arms and grows to about 20 cm across.
Carnivorous, feeds on a variety of shellfish.
Rows of sharp, long, white spines bordering the arms.
Found around New Zealand but has been introduced to southern Australia.

Usually has 5 arms. The body is olive green to brown, some are orange or blue, the underside is a lighter colour than the upper side. The tube feet end in a suction-cup-like appendage. Grows up to 8 cm across.
Breeds during summer, producing planktonic larvae.
Opportunistic omnivore, feeds by extruding the stomach through the mouth on detritus, microfilm, and a variety of shellfish .
Commonly found on rocky, sandy, and muddy bottoms down to 100 m depth.
Flattened five-sided shape. Its surface has a grainy texture. It is the most common rocky shore sea star.
Has 5 arms. The underside is a creamy white, the upper side can be bright yellow or orange, or a darker brown. Grows up to 15 cm across.
Little is known of the biology of this species.

Feeds on snails, crustaceans, and small fish. Lifts the body onto the arm tips to create a tent shape. Unsuspecting prey can enter this shelter and if the sea star's underside is touched, it will drop onto its prey, trapping it and eating it.
Can be found on rocky walls or in crevices.
Five-sided, it is larger and thicker than the common cushion star.
Round and very flat. When alive it is covered in short brown spines, giving it a velvety texture.

Breeding occurs in late summer. Eggs and sperm are released through pores on the upper side. Fertilisation occurs in the water column. Usually individuals are either male or female, but rare individuals may be hermaphrodites that have both male and female reproductive organs. Lives for up to 10 years.
Lives buried under a thin layer of fine sand. Found in sheltered bays and estuaries.
Calcareous, white, empty shells can be found on the beach, sometimes as whole round discs, sometimes broken into 'pizza slice' wedges.
Common throughout all the coastlines of New Zealand, from Stewart Island to the Three Kings.

Grows to 100-200 mm in diameter, may reach more than 250 mm in the Three Kings region. Reddish brown tube feet are interspersed with a dense covering of sharp-tipped, long, greenish spines. The feet radiate outward like slender, suckered guy-ropes. These provide a tenacious hold, and may also attach to small pieces of debris with which the urchin sometimes covers itself.

Soft tube feet pass through perforations in the plates that make up the urchin test (shell). As in all urchins these are operated by an internal water pumping system. The urchin moves about through the combined action of the long spines and tube feet. In exposed areas with heavy wave surge, spines are relatively shorter, and thicker, and brace the urchin in crevices. A mass synchronous spawning by a dense aggregation was observed in Doubtful Sound; the subsequent gamete cloud spread for 40 km. It is preyed on by rock lobsters and snapper.

Nocturnal grazer which feeds on coralline and other algae. Algae are picked off and passed through a five-toothed grinding mill called the Aristotle’s lantern, which sits just inside the test. When fishing removes its main predators, the larger rock lobster and snapper, kina can overgraze kelp beds in more sheltered sub-tidal rocky reefs, resulting in urchin barrens. Evidence from the two oldest marine reserves, at Leigh and Tawharanui, suggests that the recovery of predator numbers following marine reserve protection results in declines in sea urchins and the recovery of algal forests and communities.
On rocky coasts, from low tide to at least 60m.

A slightly flattened, light greenish test (shell) made of a mosaic of plates with regular series of small pale knobs. Moveable, dark greenish spines are attached to these knobs when the urchin is alive.
Found in temperate waters of the world, including around New Zealand.

Usually up to 60 mm, but can grow larger. A mat of furrowed yellowish or fawn spines grows from tubercles and mostly points backwards. It has a wide variety of tube feet, all of which are used in feeding and/or locomotion. The upper surface is flattened with a sunken star-shaped area. Each arm of the star is called a petal and is a specialised zone where respiratory tube-feet exit through a pair of larger pores.

Lives buried in offshore mud and sand, sometimes down to a depth of 100 to 150 mm below the sediment surface. It makes both respiratory and sanitary channels leading to the surface. The spines trap air which helps prevent asphyxiation. Burrows are marked by a conical depression on the surface in which detritus can collect.

Deposit feeder. Particles are channeled towards the mouth by spines located near the groove at the front of the urchin. They are gathered into a mucous string which is then hauled in by the movement of other spines.

Lives buried in soft mud and sand at a range of depths, from the extreme low tide mark downwards. For example, it was found down to 140 m and within most sediment types sampled in the Marlborough sounds.
Heart-shaped, with sunken star-shaped area near the centre. This species is most often seen when dead and washed ashore, and then they have usually lost the spines.
Distributed around the entire New Zealand coastline and associated islands, and found in parts of southern Australia.

Typically 130-250 mm in length. The upper surface is studded with pointed tubercles of different sizes and the colour can range from mottled greyish-brown to black. The underside is paler in colour, sometimes pinkish. This is rather flattened, with three rows of tube feet with which it moves and clings. The skin is tough and leathery, and the only traces of the calcareous skeleton found in other echinoderms are microscopic plates and spicules embedded in the skin.

A circle of 20 oral tentacles at one end surrounds the mouth. It feeds by extending these tentacles to the sediment surface, capturing particulate matter, and passing this into the mouth. It can be detected in the wild by its long smooth faecal castings of fine sand and debris. Water is taken in through the anus and then passes through a respiratory tree. This species is of commercial interest for marine farming.
Detritivore, captures nutritious organic particles from the surrounding substrate.

Inhabits a wide range of depths and a variety of habitats, from rocky reefs to mudflats. They are found in large numbers subtidally between 2 - 25m in association with reef structures in north eastern New Zealand but may be deeper in Milford Sound. When found within reefs they are often seen in crevices or depressions where sediments accumulate.
Our largest and most common sea cucumber. Sausage-shaped and 'warty'. Mottled light brown to black. Slug-like.
Found around New Zealand, also The Snares Islands.

Purplish black, the central disc is about 2 cm across, and the 5 arms are about 7 cm long. The arms have flattened arm spines on either side which look like banks of oars. Has an internal skeleton of calcium carbonate plates.
The sexes are separate. Breeding season is from spring into summer.
Captures particles from passing currents in mucus that coats the spines. The mucus is rolled into balls which are then passed into the mouth.
Under large boulders in the lower intertidal to subtidal.
Has the ability to shed arms to escape predators, and can regenerate lost arms.
Found around New Zealand and the Kermadec Islands.
The central disc is about 10-12 cm in diameter and mottled grey in colour. The five arms have brown and white bands and are about 6 cm long. Has an internal skeleton of calcium carbonate plates.

The sexes are separate. Females lay eggs which are a tenth of a mm in diameter and when fertilised these develop into larvae which live and feed for a while in the plankton. This means they can disperse over long distances.
Extends the last third of several arms out from under its hiding place and catches bottom detritus in mucus threads along the arms. These are rolled into balls which are then passed into the mouth.
In pools, under rocks, and on sand covered by rocks, in the intertidal to at least 10m depth.
Has the ability to shed arms to escape predators, and can regenerate lost arms.
Around New Zealand, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Medium-sized spider, with body length of about 1 cm. The reddish brown cephalothorax (first body segment) is almost rectangular in outline. The dusty grey abdomen is oval and slightly broader than the cephalothorax. Has two very large fangs (chelicerae) at the front of the head which are almost as long as the cephalothorax. The legs are about 1.5 times as long as its body.

Female spiders grow larger than male spiders. Most females are alone in winter, but will pair up with a male of similar size in spring. The nest is only large enough for one pair of spiders plus brood. Females probably live for more than a year, but males probably survive only for one breeding season.
Preys on small invertebrates, such as amphipods and isopods, that live near the nest.

Lives in nests in rocks and crevices, under shells, and in cavities in the holdfast of bull kelp, Durvillaea antarctica, between high tide down to about 1 m water depth. Forages for food when exposed as the tide goes out.

Lives in a waterproof nest made of silk in holes, tunnels or crevices in intertidal rocks and kelp holdfasts. When the tide comes in it spins a waterproof closure over the entrance. The air space in and around its nest is enough so that it can live underwater for at least 19 days.
Limited to sand dunes close to the seashore. Throughout most of coastal New Zealand, although not found within the southernmost regions, below about 38 degrees South.

Has black and striped colour variants. Body is about 8 mm, and leg span up to 32 mm for females, adult males 1/6 the size of females. For striped variants, a bordered stripe on an otherwise black back runs back to the spinnerets. The underside may have a red patch or partial hourglass marking. Black katipo may still have a partial abdomen mark. Juveniles have a mainly white abdomen with a series of black-bordered, orange-red diamonds on the back. Males keep this coloration. Adult males have swollen pedipalps at the front and they use these organs to transfer sperm (picture 3).

Eggs incubate for six weeks in summer in spherical cream egg sacs. Spiderlings disperse by either a bridging method where they use silk to move to nearby plants, or sometimes a ballooning method, where heat currents carry them away suspended by a single web strand. Katipo are related to Australian redback spiders, and when a male redback mates with a female katipo it produces hybrid offspring. However, as the male katipo is larger than the male redback his weight on the web triggers a predatory response from the redback female, and he is eaten before mating can occur.

Feeds on ground invertebrates including beetles and sandhoppers, also moths, flies, and spiders. Females bite the prey several times. They then move the prey up into the web until ready to eat. Webs are irregular and tangled among base of dune plants and debris.

In coastal dune systems, commonly builds webs in low growing plants and driftwood or flotsam. Stock grazing, disturbance, burning, commercial forestry, and recreation impact katipo by changing dune habitat. Marram grass, planted to stabilise dunes, has displaced native plant species and grows so densely it prevents katipo from building webs.

Venomous to humans. Often under drift wood. Female spiders from the northern part of the North Island have a totally black, round, pea-sized abdomen. Elsewhere they have a red or orange stripe down the middle.
North and South Island, from Canterbury northwards.

Up to 30 mm long. Polished black or dark brown armour. Nocturnal, never seen in bright daylight, except for its meandering tracks on damp sand and in the early morning. Adult beetles active September to November. Dead beetles will be male. The adults also fly, which they do noisily. The larvae are large (pictured) and also move about on the sand surface at night. They can be seen curled up under driftwood and among roots of plants.

Part of a genus which is unique to New Zealand. The female lays eggs deep in the sand. Larvae are salt-tolerant and live just under the sand surface above the high tide mark. The larvae are remarkable for their large, spatulate claws. These help it travel through the sand as well as on the surface of the sand during nightly foraging trips. During the day all life stages remain buried in the sand. It is preyed on by birds.

array.string: mumutaua, mumutawa, mumuwaru, mumuwharu, or ngungutawa

dict.string: Herbivorous. Presumed to feed on the roots of vegetation and decaying wood.
Occurs between the driftwood zone and first dune ridge and is sometimes common among roots of vegetation such as spinifex. Lives buried in the sand under well-anchored driftwood.
Large, massive, shining black or dark brown beetle on coastal sand dunes and beaches.

Adults grow to 27 mm long. Wingless. Deep blackish-brown and black, sometimes with orange markings. Fast-moving, vanishes quickly out of sight. The male’s powerful forceps are of unequal length, with the right more curved. The forceps of females are almost symmetrical.

Nocturnal. Common on beaches under debris and stones above high-tide mark. Females fiercely guard and protect their eggs and growing young. When danger threatens, the juveniles will shelter beneath her and she is likely to kill other approaching earwigs. However, eventually the mother turns cannibalistic, at which point the young disperse. These earwigs carry out a careful cleaning routine after feeding. Can give a painful nip with their forceps, which are used for defence and fighting, as well as foraging.
Carnivorous. Feeds on small beach insects and animals such as slaters, catching them with their large rear forceps. They are also cannibalistic, eating younger life stages.

Common on beaches under debris, stones and decaying seaweed above high-tide mark. Can also be found in gardens of Auckland suburbs. It prefers habitats with numerous crevices for hiding and avoids fine sand or soil.
Long, smooth, flattened body. Dark brown and black, large forceps which are often asymmetrical at the end of the abdomen.
North, South and Stewart Islands but most abundant in North Island. Other species are more common in the South Island.
A small velvety black fly with one pair of wings, body 2.5 to 3 mm long.

Needs flowing streams and rivers to breed. Lays eggs on stones or plants near the surface. Larvae strain food (mostly microscopic organisms) from the passing water. Makes a cocoon of solidified saliva. When the cocoon splits the newly hatched adult pops to the surface in an air bubble.
Larvae filter microorganisms from water. Adult males feed on nectar only but females feed on both nectar and blood. Original hosts were birds and seals.

Prefers higher humidity and is more common near streams and water. Females will fly long distances searching for hosts, often along beaches. Adults active spring-autumn with peak in summer. Larvae present in streams all year.

There are 19 species of sandfly known from New Zealand and some of its offshore islands, but only 3 are serious biters of humans. Only the females bite because they need blood so their eggs can develop. Known as blackflies elsewhere in the world. New Zealand species don't transmit diseases to humans.
Sandhoppers are found worldwide, and around New Zealand.

A sandhopper body is compressed from side to side and its legs are often disproportionately long. It splays the hind legs to stay upright. A notable acrobat, it can jump great distances by tucking the tail under and then flicking it out.
Herbivore. Nocturnal scavenger on decaying seaweeds.

Lives at high tide level. A sandy beach is an extreme environment for small animals, where they can be sand-blasted, drowned or dried out. Therefore, when the tide is out sandhoppers are most often found under beach-cast seaweeds which provides food, as well as protection from the sun and predators. Juvenile sandhoppers live on the surface of the sand under drift seaweed, but adults can burrow more than 10 cm into sand to avoid temperature stress and tidal inundation.
Tiny shrimp-like hopper which is abundant under decaying seaweed on sandy beaches.
New Zealand, Australia and Lord Howe Island.

Grows to 7 cm in length. Variable in colour, but usually dark (the pictured specimen has lost its colour). It has one outsize claw (chela). It has a single short, sharp spine on the front of the head shield which sticks out beyond the eyes.

Carnivore. The snap of its disproportionately large claw creates a powerful 'cavitation' bubble which creates a shock wave strong enough to stun or kill prey as large as small fish. The snap makes a noise of over 200 decibels (an aircraft at take-off produces 180 decibels of noise).
Lives under rocks from the intertidal to 25 m water depth.

Has a single large claw which it uses to make the characteristic snapping sound. Looks like its close relative, Alpheus socialis, but is bigger than this species, and the front of the head shield projects forward as a single, short sharp spine, whereas Alpheus socialis has 3 short spines.
New Zealand, Australia and Lord Howe Island.

Grows to 3.5 cm in length. Greenish. It has one outsize claw (chela). It has three short, sharp spines on the front of the head shield, one in the centre and the others on either side in line with the eyes.

Carnivore. When it snaps its disproportionately large claw a powerful 'cavitation' bubble is created that causes a shock wave strong enough to stun or kill prey as large as small fish. The snap makes a noise of over 200 decibels (an aircraft at take-off produces 180 decibels of noise).
Rocky or sandy coasts, mangrove forests, intertidal to over 100 m water depth.

Has a single large claw which it uses to make the characteristic snapping sound. Looks like its close relative, Alpheus novaezealandiae, but it is smaller than this species and the front of the head shield has 3 short spines, whereas Alpheus novaezealandiae has a single, short sharp spine.
New Zealand, Kermadec Group, Australia, South Pacific and Chile

Carapace (body armour) 60-80 mm and nearly square, leg span of 200-230 mm. It is finely corrugated and variable in colour; shining black with reddish-brown or purple streaks, or a mottled dull reddish-purple. Under-surface is white with mauve on the claws and green at the joint membranes. Legs are slender and flattened, with the upper segments smooth and strong. Red spines on the lower segments give it grip on uneven surfaces. Aggressive when cornered.
Primarily an air-breathing crab which can tolerate long periods out of water.

Omnivorous, but diet varies between localities, seasons, and size and sex of crabs. Larger males feed almost entirely on green intertidal algae. Smaller crabs feed on periwinkles and barnacles, and bigger crabs on black flea mussels, chitons and larger gastropods. After moulting they will eat large amounts of pink coralline algae, presumably for the calcium carbonate that is needed to make a new shell.
High in the marine rocky intertidal, above mid-tide level.
Large, aggressive crab found on rocky shore, will dart under large rocks or into fissures.

Olive brown to bright green shrimp, camouflaged against algae. Grows to about 4 cm. The rostrum (spine extending from the head) has a tip with 2 points and there are 2 or 3 smaller spines on the upper edge. Some specimens have small coloured tufts on the body. Often attracted to light at night.
Females have eggs from January to August.
Omnivorous, scavenges and also feeds on small seaweed fauna.
Subtidal to about 20 m, usually found with algae.
Olive brown or green, with scattered small, bright blue spots. Permanently bent body with a hump near the middle. Has very long antennae.
North, South and Stewart Islands, southeast Australia (including Tasmania).

Pale brown and covered in hairs, body up to 4 cm long, it is almost pear-shaped with 2 sharp spines at the front. Has short, hooked hairs on its back to which it attaches pieces of sponge or seaweed. The chelipeds (large claws) are slender and long, and the tips of the 'fingers' are white.
Breeds from at least September to April, and probably later in northern regions. Has a planktonic larval stage that lasts for just over a month.
Known to eat mussel spat, but probably also eats small invertebrates and seaweeds.
Sand, mud, coarse shell or rock. Intertidal to at least 35 m water depth, but can be deeper.
It is a slow mover and in order to avoid predators it camouflages itself by sticking pieces of sponge and seaweed to the hooked hairs on its back.
Species from this genus are found throughout New Zealand and overseas.

The curved and asymmetrical abdomen is not calcified, so a hermit crab adopts empty shells for protection. As it grows, larger and larger shells have to be found. The first and second pairs of legs are used for walking. One claw is larger than the other, and is used for defence. Species in this genus are not easy to identify, but Pagurus novizealandiae is grey with blue marks and fringes of dull brown hair. Hermit crabs can be the most abundant crab in pools and in muddy rock cover near low tide.

Before leaving the safety of its current home a hermit crab carefully inspects a new shell. Vacancy chains have been described for several overseas species. These chains can involve crabs in size-sorted queues, with the largest hermit crab at the head. As the largest crab shifts into a suitable vacant shell each of the other crabs move into the next largest shell in the queue.

Hermit crabs are not fussy when it comes to food. Many species employ a number of strategies, such as deposit-feeding, scavenging, predation and filter feeding. They will feed on any plants or small animals, including small gastropods and bivalves which are crushed by the teeth of the major claw and then eaten. They also feed from sea floor sediments, sifting these through the chelae (claws) and walking legs fringed with hairs. Larger particles are picked up individually and scrubbed clean of detritus by the inner mouthparts, while the major claw crushes gravel particles into smaller sizes.
This genus is found from the rocky intertidal to the outer shelf, down to at least 200 m.
Occupies empty spiral shells. Look for any spiral shell that appears to move much faster than it should.
Common throughout New Zealand and Chatham Islands.

Can reach a length of 40-75 mm. Alert, darts about with great speed when disturbed in rock pools. Has a serrated rostrum (spine) on the head. Body is transparent. The longitudinal bands of colour include green, red and black, but their overall appearance is green.
Can cope with the high salinity of rocky pools. Salinity tolerance increases directly with prawn size. When moving slowly, it may swim with its abdominal limbs and part walk on the tips of the legs.
Omivorous, will take plankton, detritus, or any material small enough for it to eat, including young of any species, and decaying plants.
Tidal rock pools, mangrove swamps, and estuaries. Frequently seen stranded in shallow pools on rock platforms.
Nearly transparent shrimp with greenish lines on body, black and orange-red spots on the base of the abdomen and legs.
New Zealand, Chatham Islands and southern Australia. As far south as the Auckland Islands.

Can grow up to 500 mm long and typically weighs 2-3 kg, but occasionally more than 8 kg. Variable colour; when alive it can be brightly marked above with reddish-purple, dark red and orange. Underside is pale yellowish or grey-green brown. No pincers, and with spiny growths on the sides of the tail. Has a pair of long serrated antennae which can rotate in all directions.

May live for more than 30 years. Sexually mature between 7–11 years. Grows by moulting; the shell and entire jointed armour is cast off in one piece. While soft-bodied it hides for a short time until a new shell forms and hardens. The localised inshore - offshore movements of mature males and females are linked to moulting and reproductive cycles. Females carry between 100,000 and 500,000 eggs under the tail where they develop for up to 6 months. They then walk into deeper water where currents are stronger for hatching. They also occasionally migrate in large numbers, moving up to 460 km.

array.string: Red rock lobster or spiny lobster

dict.string: Carnivorous. Ventures out from its rocky cover at night to feed on a wide range of prey. This includes sea stars, urchins, crabs, shellfish, small fishes, barnacles and even its own young and cast-off moults. It will also eat seaweed.
Rocky coasts and reefs, where it lives in caverns, within gaps between rocks and in other rocky shelters. Also found among seaweeds. Depth ranges from 5–200 metres.
Our most common marine crayfish and largest decapod (with 10 feet). Brightly coloured with ornamentation over body and on tail segments.
North, South and Kermadec Islands, but mainly in the North Island, and eastern Australia.

Grows to at least 60 cm in length and can weigh up to 15 kg. It has spiny growths on the head, but the abdomen is smooth. Hides in crevices during the day, especially when immature, to avoid predators.

Thought to be relatively slow growing and long-lived. Females mature when carapace is between 60 and 120 mm, depending on locality. Moult is in autumn. Larval development in the plankton takes at least a year. Immature individuals may migrate variable distances during spring and early summer. Uses chemical cues to detect and avoid predators such as octopods.

Nocturnal, active predator. Studies of related species have shown they will eat molluscs, crustaceans, echinoderms and other invertebrates, but also coralline and fleshy algae. Prey size increases with lobster growth.
Rocky coasts and sandy or gravel bottoms between 1 and 150 m depth.
Immature and small adults are green, with larger and very large individuals yellow or reddish orange. Smooth abdomen.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Muddy brown, but lighter underneath. The body is broadly oval, about 2 cm wide, and covered with a mix of short and long hairs which gives it an untidy look. There are 3 sharp, forward-facing spines on the front left and right margins of the body, but these may be hidden by the hairs. The 'fingers' on the large claws are black with white tips.

Has the shortest development period of any crab species in New Zealand. It does not have a planktonic stage and eggs hatch directly into a larval stage called a megalopa. This is carried around by the female crab for about a month until it hatches into the first juvenile crab stage.
Under boulders and in rocky crevices. Intertidal to 130m.
When disturbed, it freezes and then it is very difficult to see as its colour hides it against its background.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Body rounded and as wide as it is long. The male is orange brown with cream patches and white spots, flattish, and grows to about 1 cm wide. The female is cream-coloured and grows to about 2 cm. She is almost always in berry (carrying eggs) which makes her look more spherical and orange.
Appears to produce eggs all year round. Large females can carry about 10,000 eggs.
Feeds on food particles collected by the host species.
Parasitic in the green-lipped mussel, but has also been found in other mussel species, oysters, pipi and cockles. Intertidal to 30 m depth.

Lives with bivalve molluscs, such as green-lipped mussels, and steals the food from the gills of its host. It is considered a parasite because it damages the gills and tissues, and affects the growth rate of its host.
Southern hemisphere. North, South, and Kermadec Islands. Also, Lord Howe Island, Tonga, Australia, South Africa, Chile.

Can reach an overall width of 220 mm. Carapace (body armour) is as wide as it is long, with a shallow, semicircular central groove. Has 3 evenly-spaced, strong subtriangular spines on each side of the body. The legs are ridged. It is various shades of red, with the naked ridges on dorsal surfaces darker. Partly covered with yellowish-brown short, stiff hairs, but mostly smooth. Underside pale or creamy. Claws enlarged in mature males. Movements are very fast and it will frequently attach or feign attack.

Larger females breed slightly later than smaller females. Freshly laid eggs are orange to brick red, and light green when ready to hatch. Active from dusk onwards. Hard to capture, it can run very fast over rocks and swims rapidly underwater. Pugnacious, both males and females under study spent approximately 20% of their time in combative encounters.

A nocturnal opportunistic carnivore, it feeds mainly on limpets, chitons, mussels, and gastropods, brown algae and coralline turf. It is cannibalistic, and will also eat brittlestars and dead animals such as sea birds. Diet may be partly size-dependant, with small crabs more herbivorous, and larger crabs more carnivorous.
Low tide to 25m. Lives sub-tidally on exposed rocky coasts. Found in crevices and under ledges. Rarely seen out of water, and then only among seaweed-covered rocks at low tide.
More or less brick-red in colour, has sharp serrations on the edge of the body and is partially covered with short, stiff, brownish hairs. Legs are ridged.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Also South Australia.

Large, active, and pugnacious. Grows to 100-150 mm in width. The carapace (body armour) is wide and rounded in front, slightly convex with a smooth surface, and is sharply toothed at the margins. Speckled bluish to sandy grey, with 2 dark red-brown blotches near the bottom of the body, and 2 smaller spots towards the front. There is a small butterfly-shaped pattern in the centre. Legs pale orange, but claws have dark red-brown markings on inner faces. White underneath. Right claw is usually larger and a crusher, the left smaller and a cutter.

Mating occurs when females are soft-shelled after moult. Males defend females from other males for several days. Females can carry up to 850,000 eggs and produce up to 3 batches each breeding season. The lifecycle includes planktonic stages. Seasonal on and off-shore migrations are not well understood. Uses its paddle shaped hind-limbs to swim. If disturbed, it will defensively hold the claws aloft and then may subside quickly into the sand until only its eyes appear above the surface. Very aggressive and may nip your feet if you stand over the spot where it is hiding.

Carnivorous. Preys on any living animal small enough for it to take, which it then tears to pieces. A study of gut contents identified 72 species, including bristle worms, crustaceans, gastropods, fishes, echinoderms, and bivalves. When hunting bivalves such as toheroas, tuatuas, cockles and pipis, it excavates these from the sand and crushes the shells. Larger shellfish are tackled with techniques such as chipping at the margins of the opening edges until the crab can insert its claws into the widening gap between valves.
Beaches and sandy estuaries. It inhabits both exposed and sheltered coastlines so long as a coarse sandy substrate is available. Intertidal to 100m, but most common in upper 10m.
Crab with broad, paddle-shaped back legs adapted for swimming and digging in loose sand. The mainly smooth carapace has a toothed margin and four spots.
Around New Zealand, including Auckland Islands. Tasmania, but may have been introduced.

Carapace (body armour) flattened, oval, smooth and around 16mm long. Colour varies from black, blue, greyish or greenish. Two very large, flattened chelipeds (first legs carrying the claws). Only 3 pairs of walking legs visible. The fourth pair is reduced and partially hidden under the abdominal flap.

Breeds year round in the north, but season shortens southwards. The position of the long antennae and reduced number of walking legs shows it is not a true crab. Like crayfish, it can use the abdominal flap to swim backwards, a strategy it uses to escape predators. Quite fragile, it will also lose limbs to escape predators. These generally grow back during several moults.
Feeds on intertidal tube worms, but most of its diet consists of fine organic particles which it filters from seawater.

Upper intertidal to just below low tide. Beneath boulders in the intertidal zone, on wharf piles, between large fauna on rocky shores. Preyed on by large number of other intertidal and subtidal species.

Small, flattened, oval body with 2 outsize first legs and claws. Long slender antennae. Often found hiding in large numbers under boulders in the intertidal zone. Slightly larger, smoother and less red than Petrolisthes novaezelandiae, the red porcelain crab.
South East Asia, particularly in the waters of Japan, Korea and Malaysia. Now also invading North Island harbours and estuaries.

Carapace (body armour) is 120 mm wide and has ridges. There are six distinct spikes on each side of the eyes. In New Zealand it ranges in colour from pale green through olive green, to a deep chestnut brown with purplish markings. Most of the crabs found in the Waitemata Harbour tend to have yellow-orange and brown-orange markings on the shell and legs. They have white tips on the claws. If you suspect you have found this crab in any other location in New Zealand, report it to: 0800 80 99 66.

First reported in New Zealand in Auckland in late 2000. A survey completed in 2003 found it throughout the Waitemata Harbour. By 2009 populations up to 70 km from the likely invasion point were detected. It is now widespread in the Waitemata Harbour and wider Hauraki Gulf. One was found in Whangarei Harbour in 2003 and two further crabs were found in this harbour in 2009. It has the potential to invade many other New Zealand estuaries and harbours. An aggressive crab with a ferocious nip, it has the potential to compete with native crabs for space and food.

Carnivorous. An opportunistic predator of bivalves, fishes and a large range of benthic (sea floor) invertebrates. This invasive large crab is a significant predator and it is likely to have a significant impact on New Zealand species and ecosystems.
Estuaries and harbours with firm sand or muddy fine sand. It is expected to spread and establish populations in other harbours and estuaries on the North Island within the next decade.
This invasive crab is large with paddle-like hind legs. Adult has six spines or spikes on each side of the eyes and ridges on its carapace (shell).
Leigh to Banks Peninsula, Chatham Islands.

Body flattened and broadly oval, just over 2 cm wide and covered in short hairs which are thicker towards the ends. There are 3 short spines each along the front left and right margins of the carapace (body) but these may be hiden by the hairs. The large claws have black or dark brown 'fingers'.

Eggs hatch into a stage called a zoea that is a planktonic stage in other crustaceans, but not in Pilumnus lumpinus. It last less than an hour before it changes into the megalopa stage. During the megalopa stage it hides in crevices and amongst algae.
On rocky coasts in crevices, under boulders and any other shelter. Low intertidal.

When disturbed, it freezes and is very difficult to see as its muddy colour hides it against the background. However, it will quickly try to hide and if no cover is available it will bury itself by digging backwards into sand.

Carapace (body armour) up to 23 mm across. Drab coloured. Scuttling in large numbers on mud flats and tidal creeks. When it reaches high densities the mud surfaces will be marked with many hundreds of holes. Its quick movement presumably helps avoid predation by seabirds and fish.

Territorial, it will patrol its tunnel, challenging crabs that stray too close, posturing and sometimes blowing bubbles at opponents. The tunnels dug in the mud can form quite a complex network. This burrow building and its other sediment shifting activities means it is a bioturbating species which can affect the degree of contact between sediment and water. Unlike many other burrowing crabs, its activity is not affected by the day-night cycle.
Surface deposit-feeder. Feeds on minute particles of organic matter found in tidal mud. Will shift mud to expose food.

Known for constructing tunnels in tidal mud habitats that are exposed to the air for at least 6 hours on each tidal cycle. However, they can inhabit a wide spectrum of sediment types from silt to coarse sand with reported burrow depths of up to 60 cm. Found mid to high shore.
Scuttling, square-backed, dull coloured, often on tidal mud. Will dart down tunnels.

White tinged with pink, grows to 5 cm long. The head is large and tapered towards the front, the broad abdomen consists of several segments and is followed by a well-developed tail fan. In males one claw is enlarged, which could be either the right or the left.

Filter feeder. The last limbs on the body create a current flow through the burrow in which it lives. Fine hairs on the second and third pairs of legs then gather up organic particles from the seawater.

Makes elaborate and long, semi-permanent burrows in sand, on protected shores, from the low intertidal to the shallow subtidal. The burrows have an inhalent tunnel for the inflow of water and an exhalant tunnel for the outflow of water. The exhalant end can be recognised by the cone-shaped mound of sand at the exit.
A flexible shrimp-like animal which is quite floppy and unable to move when dug out of its burrow.
North and South Islands, but more common in the south.

Has light and dark variants. The light variant has a cream background with light or dark chest-nut red. The dark variant has purple markings which may be nearly purplish-black. The eyestalks are white. Body flattened, smooth, slightly wider than long, grows to nearly 6 cm for males, and 4.5 cm for females.

Has a very short breeding season in late autumn to winter, eggs are carried for about 3.5 months. After time in the plankton the metamorphosed juvenile crab probably settles first in the lower intertidal and moves up the shore as it grows.
Known to eat seaweeds and gastropods such as oyster borers.
Under rocks on rocky or muddy sheltered coasts, from high intertidal to about mid-intertidal.
Is fast moving and agile, hides during the day and comes out at night to feed.
Cosmopolitan in tropical and temperate seas.

Five white, calcareous plates completely surround the body which sits on top of a leathery stalk (or peduncle). The stalk is an extension of the barnacle's head and is used to attach it to any floating object. The body can grow up to about 5 cm long and the stalk varies in length but may get to over half a metre long.
Hermaphrodite. Fertilised eggs hatch inside the parent barnacle and are then released into the plankton where they spend some weeks before settling onto floating objects.
Filter feeder. Uses its feathery feeding cirri - which are actually its modified legs - to sweep organic particles and tiny organisms from the water and into the mouth.
Attaches to any floating objects, such the hulls of ships, driftwood and pumice.

Goose barnacles are so-called because they were thought to be the juveniles of barnacle geese. These migratory geese were for a long time thought not to breed and lay eggs like other geese, but to be produced by driftwood.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Also eastern Australia south of Port Jackson. Invasive species in Western Europe.
Star-shaped, greyish white, conical or tubular. Four overlapping, ridged plates make up the sides and another 4 triangular plates close off the top of the barnacle when it is out of the water.
Hermaphrodite. Fertilised eggs hatch inside the parent barnacle and are then released into the plankton where they spend some weeks before settling.
Filter feeder. Uses its feathery feeding apparatus - which are actually its modified legs - to sweep organic particles and tiny organisms from the water and into the mouth.
Lives in estuaries and on sheltered rocky shores, from the intertidal to shallow subtidal. The barnacles on mangrove roots are mostly the modest barnacle.
One of the most common fouling barnacles.
Originally native to the Pacific and Indian Oceans, but now introduced to all tropical and warm temperate seas.
Light pink to purplish pink. Grows to 2.5 cm diameter. Ranges from low conical to steep-sided, with 6 striated triangular plates. The opening at the top is roughly triangular in shape.
Hermaphrodite, and has a planktonic larval stage.
Filter feeder. Uses its feathery feeding apparatus - which are actually its modified legs - to sweep organic particles and tiny organisms from the water and into the mouth.
Grows on any hard surface, in sheltered locations, from the low intertidal to at least 55 m water depth in New Zealand.
North Island, including the Three Kings Islands, South Island north of Banks Peninsula on the east coast and north of Cape Foulwind on the west coast.

Dull greyish white. A low cone which is made up of a ring of 6 fused plates. The flat operculum (lid) is made up of 2 halves which are straight along their longest edge. Each half consists of a smaller plate (the tergum) and a larger plate (the scutum) which fit together like the pieces of a jigsaw puzzle.

Breeds in spring and summer. Hermaphrodite, and will swap sperm with other barnacles to fertilise each others eggs. As barnacles cannot move, the penis is very long so it can reach across to fertilise its neighbours.
Filter feeder. Uses its feathery feeding apparatus - which are actually its modified legs - to sweep organic particles and tiny organisms from the water and into the mouth.

Lives on rocks in the high intertidal zone. On wave-exposed shores they may be found to about 4 m above the level reached by the highest spring tides, and down the shore to about mean high tide level.

Forms a zone in the high intertidal and can be recognised by the 'jigsaw puzzle' joint (pictured) between the plates that close off the barnacle. In its close relative, Chamaesipho columna, this joint is also wavy, but much less angular.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham and subantarctic Islands.

Greyish white to yellowish brown. A tall barnacle with longitudinal folds and ridges down the sides of the cone. The operculum (lid) is made of 2 halves which are straight along their longest edge. Each half is made up of a smaller plate (tergum) and a larger plate (scutum) which are separated by a curved joint.

Breeds throughout the year. Hermaphrodite, and will swap sperm with other barnacles to fertilise each others eggs. As barnacles cannot move, the penis is very long so it can reach across to fertilise its neighbours.
Filter feeder. Uses its feathery feeding apparatus - which are actually its modified legs - to sweep organic particles and tiny organisms from the water and into the mouth.

On rocks in the mid-intertidal, on surf coasts as well as more sheltered shores. Low intertidal to shallow subtidal in estuaries and harbours. Chamaesipho columna is found in the same intertidal zone and often grows on Epopella plicatus shells.
Is tall and steep-sided on sheltered coasts and low and conical on exposed coasts.
All around New Zealand and the offshore islands, including the Kermadecs and the Auckland Islands. Also found in Australia and its offshore islands, south of the tropics.

One of our most common and widespread sea-anemones. 30-40 mm tall when open and expanded, tentacles up to 15 mm long. Tentacles are a lighter red than the dark red to red-brown body and may number as many as 150 to 200 in large individuals. Along its upper edge, at the base of the tentacles, there is a row of 24 light cobalt blue beads. At low tide the animal draws its tentacles into its mouth to prevent drying out. When the incoming tide covers the animal, its tentacles unfold.

Uses its tentacles to ensnare and sting prey. The mouth is a fleshy opening in the centre of the circle of tentacles, and leads into the stomach, which takes up about a third of the body. It can reproduce either asexually or sexually and bears live young. Young are held in the body cavity until they have grown into miniature anemones.

A voracious eater, it will take any small fishes, shrimps and shellfish that come within range of the tentacles. After capturing and stinging, the prey is swallowed whole. Any indigestible parts are later disgorged.
Abundant within the mid to high intertidal zone of rocky shores, on the shaded sides of rocks and ledges.
Deep red or reddish-brown anemone. When retracted it looks like a blob of dense jelly with a small circle of bright red-pink visible at the top. When open it has a circle of red or pink tentacles.
Mid-brown body, tentacles mottled and speckled with a light bluey grey. Grows to 1 cm across the body. The small cylindrical body widens slightly towards the double crown of stubby tentacles.

Has a symbiotic relationship with the cockle, Austrovenus stutchburyi. The cockle provides the anemone with a hard surface to which it can attach, and the anemone provides the cockle with some protection from infection by feeding on the planktonic larval stage of a parasite which infests shell fish.
Predator. Uses the stinging cells on the tentacles to capture small prey from seawater.

Grows on hard substrates, and often found stuck to the cockle, Austrovenus stutchburyi. Upper mid-intertidal to at least 5 m waterdepth. Found where there is an accumulation of fine, soft sediment. Commonly found on sheltered sandflats and in estuaries and harbours.

The mud anemone prefers to live in sandier sediment and does not like mud content over 40%. It also does not like turbid (murky) water, and is sensitive to pollutants such as copper. It is therefore used by some regional councils as one of the indicator species to help assess the health of estuaries.
North, South, Stewart, and Chatham Islands, also southern Australia.

Common. Up to 200 mm lond and up to 100 mm wide, tentacles up to 25 mm. Colours range from brownish-orange, mauve or amber-grey to light brown. The many tentacles are short and blunt, and may be pale yellowish, grey, brown or orange. The oral disc, visible when it is open, is flat and pale yellow. The surface of the column is studded with bladder-like nodules. The basal disc is smooth. Shape varies according to the mood of the animal, it may be barrel-shaped when attached or just a flabby collapsed cylinder when drifting.

Not permanently attached by its base and can attach and release itself at will. It moves by crawling or drifting in the water. It may be seen drifting among seaweeds at low tide or attached to any surface, including waving algae.
Will take any small prey that comes within range of its tentacles, including fishes, shrimps and shellfish.
Within low-intertidal pools to around 10 m on sheltered to moderately exposed coasts.
Soft and covered with many soft bladder-like nodules. When open, has many colourful short blunt tentacles.
Pale yellow to brown to olive green. Grows to 4 cm high and just over 3 cm across the body. The tentacles are about 3 cm long. The body may have longitudinal ridges but is often smooth.
Predator. Uses the stinging cells on the tentacles to capture small prey from seawater.
In rock pools and crevices, and buried in sandy sediments, on sheltered to exposed shores, from upper to mid-intertidal.
Southern hemisphere distribution, including New Zealand and its offshore islands.

Upright stems divide dichotomously (divide in two) and grow up to 12 cm high. Each stem consists of a flexible filament which is bordered by series of tiny paired envelopes. Each of these envelopes faces outward from the stem and contains a small hydroid animal called a polyp. Most of the polyps are feeding polyps, but some are specialised breeding polyps.

The breeding polyps (gonotheca ) form larger, flattened envelopes. Each has a circular opening which is surrounded by a raised collar and closed by an operculum (lid). Within these breeding cells, tiny young develop which look like jelly-fish, and which are dispersed to form new colonies. The colonies are also able to increase through asexual budding.
Predator. The feeding polyps use a small circle of tentacles to capture small organic particles and organisms.
Grows commonly amongst seaweeds in the low intertidal, in rock pools and especially on the shells of living mussels.
A yellowish-brown, fine hair-like mass which often grows on mussel shells. It is commonly mistaken for a seaweed, but is in fact a colony of small animals called hydroids.

Has a peacock-blue float with a variety of hanging structures, including stinging tentacles, that partially contract when the animal is washed ashore. The float is an air bladder generally 5 - 15 cm in length, which also acts as a sail. It trails the long, blue stinging tentacles which may be 20-30 m long in the very largest specimens.

The bluebottle is not an individual animal but a colony of thousands of hydroid animals, each with its own specialised purpose. Some have mouths and are feeders, some provide the stinging capsules, whereas others bear the sexual cells (which look like dark-blue grapes).
Carnivore. Captures swimming or floating organisms, such as small fish, by paralysing them with powerful stinging cells (nematocysts) on the tentacles.
Pelagic, inhabiting oceanic surface waters, but sometimes washed ashore in large numbers on open coasts, such as Auckland’s west coast. Most common in summer.

The bluebottle has a powerful sting even after death, but it is not deadly to humans although it may make you very sick. The sting is caused by a toxin inside thousands of small stinging cells on the tentacles. If you are stung don't rub the skin as it may pop any stinging cells that have not yet burst. The best way to treat it is by immersing the stung area in hot water. The best temperature is about 45 degrees Centigrade. It takes a little while, but the heat of the water deactivates the toxins. And of course, get medical help if you are badly stung or if you feel unwell after being stung.
Found worldwide, including in New Zealand coastal waters.

Usually less than 500 mm across, but can get much bigger. The umbrella is moderately thick and bowl-shaped. There are eight clusters of long trailing tentacles, with as many as 100 tentacles per cluster. Tentacles are fragile and easily broken off. A dense tangle of shorter arms comes off the centre of the sub-umbrella. Gives a severe sting and capable of stinging long after it has been stranded on the shore.

The Lion's mane life-cycle is divided into 4 separate stages. Three stages, the larval, polyp and ephyrae stages produce tiny animals. The fourth, the medusa stage, produces the large bells that float around at the ocean surface. The entire lifecycle takes about 1 year.
Stings and captures swimming and floating prey, such as small fishes.
Pelagic, found in open surface waters.
Umbrella-shaped body with dense mass of long, trailing tentacles.
North, South, Chatham and Auckland Islands and Australia.

Long and serpentine, up to 100 mm long. Deep green. Has parapodia (pseudo-feet), each of which has a single lobe expanded into broad paddles, giving this group of worms the common name of paddle worms. The head has two eyes and five tentacles. Has a thick muscular proboscis.

Eulalia microphylla is the most common Eulalia species on the rocky shore. It is often seen out in the open in shaded areas, moving sinuously between mussels, oysters and barnacles. It uses a long eversible proboscis to capture prey.
Active, long, dark worm with many parapodia ('pseudo feet').

Light grey, calcareous tubes which may be streaked with blue. A keel runs along the upper surface and projects as a sharp spine over the opening. The worm is bright blue near the head and pale orange towards the tail. It has a bi-lobed crown of dark blue tentacles banded with light grey, which opens out on either side of the mouth. When it withdraws into the tube a specialised operculum (lid) closes off the opening.
Spawns from late spring to early autumn. Larvae prefer to settle with others of this species.
Filter feeder. Uses the feathery crown to strain particles from the seawater when the tide is in.
Sheltered bays and estuaries, from the mid-intertidal to low tidal, where it cements to rocks and other hard surfaces, including pebbles and shells, as single tubes or as dense coral-like reefs.
A common fouling species that used to be more commonly known as Pomatoceros caeruleus.
Mediterranean Sea, and the European Atlantic coast north to Normandy, southern and western Australia. In New Zealand found in Auckland's Waitemata Harbour and Port of Lyttelton.

Has a single spiralled white fan striped in brown and orange. The long thin parchment tube can be as long as 400 mm. An invasive species, it was first identified at Port of Lyttelton in 2008 and shortly after was found in Auckland's Viaduct Basin. An intensive eradication programme has failed to stop its spread. If you believe you have found this pest anywhere in Northland, please call the Northland Regional Council's environmental hotline 0800 504 639. For suspected finds anywhere else in New Zealand (apart from Lyttelton and the Waitemata) please call MPI on 0800 80 99 66.

Overseas it has been shown it can alter existing marine ecosystems when it reaches high numbers. In high densities it can alter the flow of water as well as filter enormous quantities of water per day. It therefore competes with other organisms for space and food.
Grows on rocky shores and any other hard surfaces, including other organisms. Prefers sheltered, nutrient-enriched waters, intertidal to 30m depth.
Has a spiralled striped fan which projects from a long thin parchment-like tube. The tube is often muddy or overgrown with other organisms.
