A fragile tapered tube which has both ends open. Up to 5 cm long. The tube is made of fine sand grains, cemented edge to edge, of whatever sand is available in the worm's environment. The worm itself is tapered to fit the tube and has a 'cage' of golden bristles at the broader, head end.

Spawns in late summer, larvae have a planktonic stage, but it is not known how long they stay in the plankton. Once it settles on suitable sediment the young worm grows rapidly and has a life cycle and lifespan of about 1 year.
Deposit feeder. Lives buried, head-down, in soft sediments from which it selects organic particles.
In soft sediments, from mid-intertidal on semi-sheltered shore to subtidal on the inner continental shelf.
Grows rapidly and lives for about 1 year. Tubes are often found washed up on sheltered shores and harbours.

A cylindrical, tapering worm which is covered in a thick layer of colourless jelly-like mucus. The mucus is so thick that it may be hard to see the bristles which stick from either side of the body, as well as the delicate gills near the head and the long retractable palps around the mouth.
The flabelligerids are one of the few bristle worm families to have a green blood pigment. Little is known about the reproduction of this species.
Under stones in sheltered places, intertidal to shallow subtidal.
Looks like an elongate blob of colourless jelly underneath stones, but it will move quite quickly when exposed to light.

Has grey, fibrous papery tubes with an opening at either end, but which are occasionally branched. The worm has a body which is divided into 3 regions. The head region contains the feeding mechanisms as well as specialised glands that make the tube. The large segments of the mid-region fit snuggly inside the tube and act as pistons to pump water through the tube. The posterior segments contain the reproductive organs.
Sexes are separate and has a long-lived planktonic larval stage.
Filter feeder. Creates a mucus net that traps organic particles. The net is rolled up into a ball which is moved along into the mouth.

In coralline turf on shore platforms, and partly buried in sediment which ranges from soft sands to coarse shell gravels. From sheltered to open coasts, and from the low intertidal to 60 m water depth.
Lives in papery tubes which wash up on beaches, sometimes in their thousands, and which are occasionally mistaken for toilet paper.
Bright pink, grows to 30 cm high. An upright, branching sponge with a fibrous skeleton which grows from a narrow base. The surface is studded with spiky projections (conules), but otherwise smooth.
Attaches to hard surfaces, from the intertidal to 60 m water depth.
Has a very characteristic bright pink colour, and lacy appearance.
North Island and northern offshore islands.

Deep rose pink, grows to 3 cm. Small solitary spherical sponge with an uneven surface texture, and several 2-3 mm oscules (exhalant siphons) near the top of the sphere. Feels granular and waxy to touch. Attaches to rock by short thick filaments.
Produces asexual buds on long filaments from July to January.
On vertical rock faces and under overhangs, from the intertidal to 30 m water depth.
Rosy pink on the outside and a dull yellow inside.

Some species are brightly coral pink to reddish brown, while others are duller brown, black-brown to steel grey. May be over 100 mm long, often found in coiled clusters of several individuals. Unlike garden worms or marine bristle worms, these worms are unsegmented. The long proboscis, or introvert, everts from an opening just above the mouth and is used to inject prey with venom.

Ribbon worms are one of the least studied groups in New Zealand. They lack a body cavity and lack a heart, and use muscle contractions to move fluids around the body. Many have some light sensitive oceli (simple eyes) on the head.
Under stones or in crevices in close contact with moist silt.
Most of the species in New Zealand are thought to be endemic.
Unsegmented. Pink or brown worms. Found in moist areas.

A large sponge, which has 2 growth forms. It occurs as an excavating sponge which bores into shells and rock. This stage is recognised only by the thin yellow fingers that stick up through rock or shells. It also occurs as a thick sheet which can reach 1 m across and which is bright yellow to orange in colour. Oscules (inhalant siphons) with raised edges are distributed over the surface and it is firm to the touch.

Needs calcareous substrates, such as shells and rocks containing calcium carbonate. Found intertidally in shaded places, subtidally in a wide variety of habitats. From mid-intertidal to at least 30 m water depth.
A common sponge which is an important bio-eroder as it uses chemicals to bore into rock and shells. Often seen as sheets of orangy yellow sponge coating rock surfaces.
Throughout New Zealand , also southeastern Australia.
Orangey brown anemone with white or light green stripes. The shortish tentacles are white. Grows to 2 cm across.
Can reproduce sexually where spawn is released into the plankton, or asexually where the anemone produces a clone of itself.
Predator. Uses the stinging cells on the tentacles to capture small prey from seawater.
On hard substrates, in rock pools and under wharfs, intertidally in shaded or sheltered locations, but subtidally out in the open. Found to at least 20 m water depth.
When it is under stress, long whip-like filaments (called acontia) that are loaded with stinging cells may appear from pores on the column of the anemone.
East and west coasts of the northern North Island.

Light to dark brown, or orange brown, up to 10 cm across and 8 cm high, found as individuals or in clusters. Globular in shape, with a smooth or warty surface texture. May have several oscules (exhalant siphons) scattered over the surface. Firm and feels slightly granular to the touch.
Produces large buds asexually from February to April and these stay attached to the parent sponge. Also reproduces sexually, and sexes are separate.
It is often found in large numbers in northern harbours.
Eastern North Island from North Cape to East Cape, South Island east coast, south coast and west coast as far north as Jackson Bay, also Chatham Islands. Southern Australia, Malaya.

Yellowish brown to purply brown, clusters of hollow, untidy cone-shaped sponges with a single large oscule (exhalant siphon) on the side or near the top of the cone. Low papillae give the surface a puckered texture, but very spongy to the touch.
Needs hard surfaces, such as rocks or ships' hulls, from the low intertidal to 20 m depth.

This sponge has been found in many places around New Zealand as well as around the western Pacific. The 'cf.' placed before the species name is short-hand to show this sponge is closest to the species described as Haliclona clathrata, but that there is some uncertainty if it really is this species. Further investigation may show that there could be several species.
North, South, Stewart, and Chatham Islands.

Sponges in this genus are usually spherical to almost spherical, with a radial skeleton. Colours may range from bright orange to yellow or rose-pink. They can measure between 20–70 mm in diameter. Although some species may be soft, most are fairly firm to the touch and just compressable. They are usually found as single spheres, but may fuse together. The surface may be marked by polygonal 'warts'. Some may become encrusted with coralline algae and bryozoans.

This genus has unusually high diversity along the coasts of Australia and New Zealand and up to one third of all known species come from this area. Many of these are only found in New Zealand. These sponges may occur in clusters of up to 50 or more.
Filter feeders, that filter food from the seawater which flows through the pores and channels in sponges.

They are found from the intertidal down to more than 30 m. Common on coasts of all degrees of exposure. Generally found in shaded positions, such as under intertidal boulders or overhangs, and subtidally on boulders, canyon walls or under ledges.
Colourful, globular sponges, resembling a golf ball.

Bright orange, thick crusts to low mounds up to 23 cm across and 4 cm high. Sponges in sheltered spots may be covered in 5-7 mm high papillae which are the siphons that draw seawater into the sponge. On exposed coasts sponges may be smooth. Soft, spongy and granular to the touch.
Filter feeder. Draws in seawater through small inhalant papillae and expels used water through larger exhalant siphons called oscules.
May be common in the intertidal zone, in harbours, rock pools and on the steep sides of surge channels on exposed coasts, occasionally found in the shallow subtidal on rocky shores.
Throughout New Zealand, from Three Kings to Stewart Island.

Sponges in this genus are upright and digitate (fingerlike), sometimes encrusting, and rarely solid. Colours range from orange to brown. The fingers spread unevenly upward from a stout stalk. They are blunt at the end and round in cross-section, and can be up to 300 mm high and and up to 20 mm wide. They feel felty.
Sponges are among the most primitive of multicellular animals, as they have no true tissue or organs. They play an important ecological role by filtering vast quantities of water.
Filter feeders, that filter food from the seawater which flows through the pores and channels in sponges.
Found within open rock reef flats with less than 10 mm sediment cover. 5 m to 50 m depth.
Common sponges with branching upright fingers.

Found throughout New Zealand. Southern hemisphere, circumpolar distribution in temperate and subantarctic waters. An invasive species in Spain, France, Britain and Ireland. First detected in northern hemisphere in 2002. Transported via shipping.

A solitary sea squirt (as opposed to colonial), although it can occur in clumps. Often 35 mm across, can be as much as 150 mm in the subantarctic. Semi-transparent, but varies in colour from clear, white, orange to brown. Can also vary in shape as the body can mould into any available space, but out in the open it will grow into an oval shape. It has two openings, for the inhalant and exhalant siphons. The siphon tips are usually orange, but not always.
Breeds from beginning of spring to the end of summer. Can self-fertilise, and broods the embryos before they are released. Larvae often settle close by.
Attached to rock faces and other hard surfaces from low water mark.
Smooth-surfaced, translucent, pale and jelly-like, attached to rock. Has 2 openings (syphons) with pale orange tips.

Wrinkled, leathery test (body) that looks like a shriveled potato. Ranges from light orange to cream. Two conical siphons have four magenta bands just inside the opening, which look like dark crosses when the siphons are closed. The branchial (inhalant) siphon is the longer siphon. Often found in cracks or crevices and firmly attached by its long base, with its two siphons facing outwards.
Little is known about the biology of this species.
Attached to rock faces and other hard surfaces from low water mark.
Tough, wrinkled test (body), light orange to cream, attached to rock or another hard surface.

Native to the northwest Pacific, including Japan, Korea, North China and Siberia. A worldwide invader of temperate waters, it is now found on the east and west coasts of North America, Europe, Australia and New Zealand. In New Zealand it has established in many ports, marinas and bays of the North Island and has also been identified in ports of Lyttelton, Christchurch and Dunedin.

Grows up to 160mm long. Has a plant-like appearance, consisting of an elongated, cylindrical body on top of a stalk. Two short siphons toward the top point upward, each with a 4-lobed opening. The body has conspicuous nodules and rounded swellings on the upper portion and rounded longitudinal ridges on the lower half. Colour varies, including brownish-white, yellowish-brown, reddish-brown, or yellowish-grey.

Has both male and female reproductive organs but does not self-fertilize. An immobile filter feeder that lives on the ocean floor or attaches to any firm object covered by sea water. It is hardy, can withstand salinity and temperature fluctuations, and easily establishes wherever it is introduced. Capable of reaching densities of 500 to 1500 individuals per square metre, it can potentially out-compete native species for space and food, and it also provides additional predation pressure on native larvae.
Filter feeder, traps particles out of the sea water.
From below low tide to at least 25m. Low energy coasts and sheltered areas. Attaches to any firm surface including rocks, pylons, hulls, buoys and pontoons. May also attach to other organisms.
Large and club-shaped. A tough leathery body with conspicuous bumps and two siphons at one end.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Commonly 60–80 mm across, but can exceed 120 mm. Reddish-brown mottling on a whitish background or ribs with intermittent dark reddish-brown markings. The flat hinge typically has 6–8 chevron-shaped hinge teeth on either side of a slightly projecting beak. The internal surface is smooth and white, but may have brown or purple patches. On worn, older shells the exterior brown colour is often worn off and only visible over the lower half or third.

Little is known about its biology. It is likely a very long-lived species, which lives half buried in sand and shelly beds. Can be found packed closely together in large numbers, but in less favourable areas can be found as soletary individuals. In Auckland waters Tucetona beds once ranged down to the Rangitoto and Motuihe Channels. Dead shells are frequently washed ashore on local beaches.
Filter feeder. Gills act as a sieve filtering particles from the water.
At or just below surface of coarse sand or fine gravel, and in shelly channels. Can tolerate moderate silt. Below low water to more than 100 m.
Large, broad, thick and heavy. Almost circular. Usually yellowish fawn to rust-coloured outside, decorated with radial ribs crossed with fine lines. Shiny interior.

Large. From 50 up to 100 mm long, although deep water shells tend to be smaller, sometimes less than 50 mm. Valves not very inflated, thickness when valves are together is 8.5-17 mm. Smooth, white and covered by a thin yellowish-brown periostracum (skin). Oval concentric growth lines visible. Inside, two small and one large muscle scars. Smooth and polished, apex towards one end. The shell gapes slightly at both ends.

Lives deeply buried in sand. The mantle edges are fused except for a gape where the long, fused and hardened siphons exit. The siphons reach to the surface, where water is drawn in through the inhalant siphon and spent water is expelled through the exhalant siphon. Usually only seen when shells wash up on the beach.
Filter feeder, filters suspended particles from the seawater.
Lives in sub-tidal sand off oceanic beaches, from shallow water to 50 m depth.
Large, thin, elongate bivalve, sides almost parallel, rounded ends.

Shell rather large, up to 6 cm long, thin, compressed, the posterior end is longer and pointier, and the anterior end is shorter and rounder. It may have 2 'folds' which run from the beak (apex) to the posterior edge, and another 3 or 4 much weaker folds which run from the beak to the anterior edge. Has fine concentric growth lines.
Filter feeder. Has 2 long siphons which extend up to the surface of the sand. One siphon draws in seawater from which food is collected. Used water is expelled by the other siphon.
Lives deeply buried in sand, below low tide on open beaches. Common, but often only seen as washed up dead shells.
Wedge-shaped, pure white, but may have traces of a thin, olive yellow periostracum (skin) particularly near the margins.
Originally from southeast Asia, and first recorded in Waitemata Harbour in 1978, it is now found in several harbours in the North Island and is spreading.
Small, olive to brownish green mussel, can grow to 35 mm. Has darker lines which radiate out from the beak (apex) and often also has a pattern of darker concentric zigzags.

Matures in about 9 months and can live for 2 years. Eggs and sperm are released into the water where fertilisation occurs. Larvae live in the plankton for 2-8 weeks before they settle, preferably on soft sediment. It then digs itself into the sediment and only the posterior end of the shell is visible at the sediment surface. It builds a nest of threads that bind the sediment.
Suspension feeder. Has 2 short siphons, one draws in seawater from which food is collected, the other expels the used water.
Prefers intertidal to shallow subtidal soft sediments, but will also settle on hard substrates, to a depth of 20m.
Invasive species in many parts of the world. Forms dense mats of many 1000s (sometimes 10,000s) of shells packed closely together. Has the ability to alter the ecology of an area.
Throughout New Zealand, also western, southern and eastern Australia.
Small, up to 30 mm. Fairly solid, smooth, shining black, sometimes blue-black. Interior bluish and semi-iridescent. Apex blunt.
Common small mussel that forms dense mats on upper tidal rock platforms and rock faces on open coast. Can tolerate sand scour as well as a considerable time out of seawater.
Filter feeder, filters plankton out of sea water.
Small, shining black, oblong shell that narrows to a blunt tip.
Cosmopolitan, found in many temperate and subtropical waters worldwide, including New Zealand.

61-118 mm long, 31 -63 mm wide, 23-53 mm thick. Sharply pointed at one end and wide at the other. The moderately inflated valves give this mussel a slightly plump profile. Colour is very dark blue to black and the outside surface is sculptured in very fine concentric growth lines. A narrow hinge plate at the anterior end has several small teeth. Interior is grey-blue to violet-black and inner zone is clouded. The muscles scars are close together.

Attaches itself firmly to hard substrate with byssus threads. May host a parasitic pea crab. Three closely related species of Mytilus occur widely in many temperate and subtropical regions of the world. These have spread naturally as well as through human activities. It is likely that the New Zealand blue mussel consists of a complex of indigenous and non-indigenous, as well as hybridised populations of these species.
Filter feeder, filters plankton out of sea water.
Lower half of rocky intertidal zone.
Moderately large and solid. Widely rounded at one end, tapering to a sharp point at the opposite end. Dark blue to black.
North, South and Stewart Islands, though more abundant in the north.

Shell very large and inflated. Can grow to at least 200 mm long. Periostracum (skin) of dark brownish-green to clear green towards edge, with russet-brown to paler brown at the tip. Near the tip brown byssus threads may grow from between the valves. Some fine concentric growth lines visible on the outside. Internally, the shells are generally pale grey-blue and slightly iridescent.

Likes hard surfaces to attach to, but on sandy bottoms it uses byssus threads to anchor to shell fragments and gravel. Supports a valuable aquaculture industry, with most of the seed mussels sourced as wild spat collected from Ninety Mile Beach. Host to the parasitic pea crab, Pinnotheres novaezelandiae. Fossils from the lower Pliocene onwards.
Filter feeder, filters plankton out of sea water.
Low tide to about 40 m. Rocky shores and wharf piles, but also on sandy substrates when gravel and shell fragments are available for anchorage.

Large and elongate. Orange brown near the tip grading to green along the wider edges of the shell, giving it the common name of green-lipped mussel. Often decorated with reddy brown radiating stripes.
Native to Pacific coast of Asia. Now also introduced to North America, Europe and east coast of Australia. In New Zealand it is throughout the North Island and found at the top of the South Island.

Large and heavy. 100-150 mm, but as big as 200 mm. Variable shape. On the outside creamy or off-white with purple splashes. Younger oysters have purple radial streaks, from narrow lines to almost solid colour. Inside it is a smooth white with purple splotches around muscle scars. Lower valve is weakly corrugated. Upper valve can have radial folds and layers formed during growth. Edges of the valves may be very thin and sharp. Valves lack the small beads (chromata) either side of the hinge of the native rock oyster.

Invasive species first noted in Mahurangi Harbour in 1971. Introduced from Asia to north America and the Australasia-Pacific regions. Can grow into dense aggregations which exclude native intertidal species. Also found individually.
Filter feeder, filters plankton out of sea water.
Low intertidal and shallow subtidal on hard surfaces. Oysters may attach to other oysters in increasingly large groups, enabling them to also invade soft substrates.
Upper valve is almost flat and fits onto a cupped lower valve. Dirty white with purple lines or splashes of colour.
Northern half of North Island, with occasional records from further south and the Chatham Islands. Also in southeast Australia, west Africa and through the Indo-West Pacific to southern Japan.

White outside with patches of purple and brown where layers are eroded. Variable shape. Cements lower valve to the rocks, and after death, this is often left behind. When alive, the upper valve fits tightly to the lower valve, matching corrugations. Valves have small beads (chromata) on either side of the hinge.

May produce 20–60 million eggs in one season, but only a small fraction reach maturity. When it spawns, eggs and sperms are cast adrift in the sea. Soon after fertilisation, eggs develop into free-swimming planktonic larvae.
Filter feeder, filters plankton out of sea water.
On hard surfaces within the mid intertidal rocky zone, including wharf piles. Sheltered sections of open coast, harbours and estuaries. Can grow in densely packed beds.
Solid shell of variable shape, cemented to rock or other hard surface. Chalky white with violet to bluish-black on the shell edges.
North Island and northern South Island.
More or less rounded outline, 40–50 mm across. The colour of the upper valve ranges from white to apricot or gold. Its shape is determined by the contour of its substrate. Not a true oyster.
The hole in the lower valve is where it attaches to the substrate via a strong, calcified extension of the foot called a byssus.
Filter feeder, filters plankton out of sea water.

Low intertidal to over 30 m. Attached to hard or firm surfaces, including other individuals. Several attached individuals can sometimes form a 'stack'. May also be found singly in soft sediments. Found commonly around Auckland.
Delicately coloured, often golden, thin, wrinkled upper valve. Lower valve is white or greenish with an oval hole near the hinge.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Almost circular in outline and resembles a fan with wide, flat-topped radial ribs on both of the valves. The upper, flat valve usually fits snugly inside the lower, convex valve. The hinge is large and straight at the base of the fan. Found in a wide range of reddish or pinkish brown colours and with a variety of patterns (zigzag, flecked, lined). When alive, tentacles and rows of small metallic blue, light-sensitive eyes are visible around the mantle edge when the shell is slightly open.

Usually up to 120 mm, but can reach more than 150 mm. Scallops are hermaphrodite - the roe consists of both white (male) and orange (female) organs. Larvae spend a short time in the plankton before settling. It takes 2–3 years to reach the legal harvestable size of 100 mm wide. Can swim through jet propulsion. By opening the shell to take in water then suddenly closing it with a snap it sends out a jet of water that propels it forwards. This is used to escape predators and an entire scallop bed may relocate through this method.
Filter feeder. Plankton suspended in seawater is trapped by mucus on the gills and then transported by cilia to the mouth.

Occurs in patches throughout New Zealand on muddy and sandy flats. Found in sheltered bays, harbours or in deeper water, from below low tide to 90 m. Juveniles can be completely buried below the sediment surface, but larger scallops may have 5–10 mm of their margin visible.
Large. One valve is convex and the other one flat. Both valves carry a fan-like arrangement of wide, flat radial ribs.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Fan-shaped, up to 5 cm across, with 2 equal, slightly convex valves. Has narrow radial ribs of varying strengths, and 2 unequal 'ears' alongside the beak (apex). The lower valve has a notch below one of the ears where the byssus threads come out. These attach the shell to rocky substrate.
Under rock, where it attaches itself with strong byssus threads. From low intertidal to 40 m depth.
One of our most colourful shells, it comes in a range of colours from lemon yellow, red-orange, lilac, grey, black, purple or purple striped with white.

Our largest bivalve. Grows to 300–450 mm long. Valves are thin and brittle. Purplish-black or purple-brown in colour with a metallic lustre at the pointed, anterior end. The outside surface has ridges ornamented with short, hollow spines. Older parts of the shell are relatively smooth, with spines getting longer as the shell grows. The hinge runs along one side. When in the sand, the shell is kept shut by the posterior adductor muscle and the weight of the sand around it. Can be found in dense beds.

Lives buried, pointed end down, in mud or soft sand. It attaches to stones, rocks or shells in the sediment with a dense growth of byssus threads. The broad end sticks out a few centimetres above the sand, with the valves agape. This visible end is often cloaked in epiphytic algae or fauna, because it provides a hard surface in otherwise soft, mobile substrate. The thick yellow-brown lips of the mantle are visible through the slightly open shell and can be protectively retracted when disturbed. If removed from the substrate, it is unable to dig itself back in.
Filter feeder. Filters suspended particles from the sea water with its gills. These have special sorting and rejecting cilia. Strings of sediment are bound up as pseudofaeces and expelled.
In soft mud or soft sand from low tide down to over 60m. Found on harbour flats or in deeper water off more exposed coasts. Confined to softer patches beyond low water on protected sand beaches.
Large, long thin shell. Narrow and pointed at one end, wide and blunt at the opposite end. The outside of the shell is dark and the inside is iridescent.

Creamy white, with a thin yellowish periostracum (skin), the beak (apex) is often purplish. A solid shell, which grows to about 5 cm across. Inflated, triangular, beak (apex) in the centre. There are 2 strong folds which run from the beak, one to the anterior edge, the other to the posterior edge. The area between the posterior fold and the edge of the shell is flat.
Lives buried in sand in shallow water off sandy ocean beaches. After storms it may be washed ashore in large numbers on west coast beaches.
Four of these shells placed with beaks (apices) to the centre make a perfect circle.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham Islands and some subantarctic islands.

Very common species. Up to 100 mm long, more likely 60-80 mm. Strong, moderately thick shell. Outside is white and covered with a thin yellowish periostracum (skin) that may be partially eroded. It may also be rust-stained, or brown, grey or black from anoxic muds. Internally, the valves are smoothly white. Variable in shape but always close to symmetrical and much longer than high, with rounded ends.

Juveniles are found higher up on the shore and they move down as they grow. Beds may reach densities as high as 1,000-2,000 per square metre. Uses its muscular foot to bury itself in soft sediment. Can also move some distance by floating on tidal currents, kept afloat up by a buoyant string or sheet of mucus it has secreted.
Filter feeder, filters plankton out of sea water.

Mid-intertidal down to at least 10-12 m. Lives buried or just below the surface in sandy or silty mud. In dense beds one end may stick above the sand. Likes areas where there is a reasonable amount of water movement, such as semi-sheltered beaches, and the mouths of estuaries.
Elongate, with rounded ends and almost symmetrical with the apex in the middle of the hinge.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands, but more common in the north.
White, solid, 6-8 cm long, 2 equal wedge-shaped valves, with the beak (apex) off-centre and closer to the posterior edge than the anterior one. Has a thin yellowish periostracum (skin).

Sexes are separate, it is a broad-cast spawner which synchronises the release of eggs and sperm into the water where eggs are fertilised. The planktonic larvae settle after 2-3 weeks. These are thought to settle in the high intertidal and to make their way down the beach as they grow. They reach adult size in about 3 years.
Lives buried just below the surface in the clean fine sand of ocean beaches, in the lower intertidal to shallow subtidal.

Closely related to the pipi. However, in pipi the beak (apex ) is central but in tuatua it is off-centre. A second species, Paphies donacina, is very similar in appearance but more commonly found in the south.
North and South Islands, the main beds used to be along the North Island west coast.

Creamy white shell with a yellowish periostracum (skin), large, up to 12 cm long, fairly solid but thin-shelled when compared with tuatua. The beak (apex) is off-centre and closer to the posterior end then the anterior one. When the equal valves are together there is a gap at the posterior end of the shell, which also has a double ridge.

Sexes are separate, it is a broad-cast spawner which synchronises the release of eggs and sperm into the water where eggs are fertilised. The planktonic larvae settle after 10-12 days. Bands of juveniles settle just below high watermark and they make their way down the beach as they grow. They reach maturity in about 2 years and may live to over 20 years.

Lives buried about 15 cm below the surface in clean fine sand between the tide marks of exposed surf beaches. Toheroa beds are best where the beach is backed by dunes with some freshwater run-off to the sea. This promotes the growth of diatoms and other small plant plankton which are the toheroa's food. Toheroa are able to migrate and may move more than 30 m in one night.

Closely related to pipi and tuatua, but the toheroa is the largest, and now also the rarest, species in the genus. In the past toheroa were found in dense beds which sometimes stretched for many kilometres.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Whitish, with rays of violet or reddish purple which radiate out from the beak (apex). Inside, the shell is violet or purplish. 4-6 cm long. Shell solid, elongate, with the beak (apex) in the centre of the dorsal edge of the shell and with a weak fold running from the beak to the angular posterior end. The anterior end is rounded. Has a golden brown periostracum (skin) which has usually been worn off by the time shells are found on the beach.
Surface deposit feeder. Has short siphons that reach to the surface and suck small particles off the surface of the sand.

Lives buried at about 5 cm below the surface of sediment. Can live in a wide range of sediment types, but often found buried in coarse sand or gravel of channels where currents sweep away finer sediment. On semi-sheltered coasts, in shallow water to 80 m depth, but most often found in depths less than 25 m.
There are several species of sunset shell in New Zealand, but Gari stangeri is the sturdiest. The others are rather thin-shelled.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham and Auckland Islands.

Very common. Rotund and solid. 47–56 mm high, 51–62 mm wide, and 39–42 mm thick. Tending towards circular. Outside whitish, tinged with pale purplish-brown, may have rust-coloured stains. Is sculptured with many strong, curved, radial ribs, cross-hatched with concentric ridges. Inside, smooth white with a violet blotch.

Not a true cockle. Lives buried in soft, muddy to fine sands, either just beneath the surface or with one side of the valves exposed just above the soft sediment. Uses the muscular foot to bury itself, and can also use the foot to crawl across the surface of the sand. Will form large colonies, however recreational collecting and habitat change have led to the loss of some beds.

Filter feeder. It sucks water down an inhalant siphon and suspended particles are trapped in mucous from which they are removed by cilia near the edges of the gills. Spent water is returned through an exhalent siphon. When found in large densities cockles have a profound effect on water quality. At Pauatahanui Inlet cockle beds filter 1.6 million cubic metres of water on each tidal cycle.
Upper mid-tide to low tide, to at least 5 m waterdepth. Found where there is an accumulation of fine soft sediment. Commonly found in sheltered sandflats and estuaries, and harbours.
Solid, rather inflated shell which feels heavy in your hand for its size. Heavy radiating ridges on the outside are crossed by finer concentric lines.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Cream coloured, often with a violet tinge to the beak (apex). Can grow to almost 9 cm. Shell large, solid, fairly convex, with a sculpture of concentric frills which often have weak spines at the posterior end of the shell.
Not a lot is known about the biology of this species, but the sexes are likely to be separate, and the larvae are likely to have a planktonic stage.
Lives buried in fine clean sand on coastal beaches, it is found in a distinct zone between 6 and 9 m water depth, but can be as deep as 15m water depth. Usually found as dead shells on the beach.
This species is not an active burrower and the frilled edges and spines on the outside of the shell help anchor it in the sand.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. More common in the north.

White or lightish brown, grows to almost 7 cm across. Shell rather large, solid, almost circular in outline but with distinct angle at the posterior end. Has 19-20 fine, even, concentric ridges per cm which makes the shell feel silky to the touch .
Not a lot is known about the biology of this species, but the sexes are likely to be separate, and the larvae are likely to have a planktonic stage.
In sand off coastal beaches, between 6 - 10 m water depth in the North Island and 5 - 8m in the South Island. Most often seen as washed up shells on the beach.
There are several species of Dosinia in New Zealand, but Dosinia subrosea is the only one with a distinct angle on the posterior edge. The others are all much rounder.
North Island and northern South Island, western, southern and southeastern Australia.

May be longer than 500 mm. Soft bodied, with eight short, sucker-bearing arms and two longer arms. Body oval and stout, with long fins along each edge. Fins are widest at midpoint. Under the skin down the middle it has a gladius, which is an internal membranous shell remnant, very like a feather with a keeled shaft. It can change colour pattern rapidly, but generally yellowish-white to dark red-brown, spotted with violet, the back may be decorated with lighter bands or spots. A bluish line on the dorsal surface outlines the body.

Short life-span. Lives up to 280 days, as measured by incremental growth rings in statoliths (tiny balancing stones), which are found within the cartilage of the skull. Juveniles may be seen in shallow water, swimming in arrow-head formation.
Found inshore in shallow coastal waters to 85m depth.
Has eight short and two longer arms. Broad flange, or fin, each side of body.
Found in temperate to tropical waters of the southern hemisphere.

The shell is white with sepia on the first parts of the spiral, very large specimens get to over 20 cm across. The shell is thin and fragile, with nodules in spiral rows. The female animal is a small octopus, with a rounded body and 8 arms, and she can grow to 10 cm. The male is much smaller at no more than 2 cm. Only the female makes the paper nautilus shell with specialised glands on a dorsal pair of arms.

The paper nautilus case is a brood chamber made by the female for her eggs and she also lives in it. The much smaller male uses a specialised arm which is huge in comparison to himself to transfer a packet of sperm to the female. After this, the arm breaks off and he dies. The female lives much longer than the male and can produce several broods of offspring.

Carnivore. Feeds on small molluscs, crustaceans, jelllies and salps which live near the surface of the ocean. It captures prey with its tentacles and then bites it to inject poison from a salivary gland.
The paper nautilus animal is a small oceanic octopus, and like other octopuses it can change colour to avoid predators.
North, South, Stewart and the Chatham Islands. Also south Australia.

Up to 2 m long. A large-bodied, long-armed and very knobbly species, completely without a shell. The beak-like jaws in the middle of the animal are the only hard parts. Arm pairs of unequal length, with the arm pair at the back the longest and the arm pair at the front the shortest. Colour and texture change, from reds and oranges to greys, but almost always with a trace of bluish spots along the arms. The male’s third right arm is modified and used in reproduction. Swims by forcing a jet of water from the siphon, the legs trail behind.

Relies on camouflage to match its background and uses muscles in the skin to change the texture of the mantle to achieve a greater match. If disturbed can cloud water with an inky fluid, but will only release ink if hard pressed. Will take prey, such as scallops, back to a den to eat at leisure. These dens can be distinguished by the pile of accumulated shells outside. Octopods possess high acuity, lensed eyes and have a sophisticated tactile ability. Individuals demonstrate personalities in behavioural lab work, as well as play and problem solving.
Carnivorous. Feeds mostly on shellfish but will take a range of prey — nocturnal predation of juvenile spiny lobsters has been caught on film.

Intertidal to 200 m. It is most often found under ledges and in deep fissures at low water on soft substrata, particularly near scallop beds. It creates its lair by excavating a hole in the sea floor which is often surrounded by the empty shells of its prey.
Has eight sucker-bearing arms of variable length. Variable colour.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands, but especially along the west coasts. Found throughout the tropical and sub-tropical Atlantic and Indo-West Pacific.

Shell is white, about 2 cm across, an open spiral in a flat plane, and rather fragile. The shell is hollow and has partitions, each of which is connected by a thin tube that allows the animal to fill the separate chambers with gas. The living animal is squid-like, cylindrical, and has 8 short arms and two longer tentacular arms. It's body is about three times as long as the shell. The shell is found at the posterior end of the animal which means that it floats head-down.

Not much is known about the life history of this squid, but eggs are less than 2 mm across. It is thought they are laid on the ocean floor since the tiniest Spirula animals, just over 2mm long, have all been captured in deep water. Isotope analysis of Spirula shells showed they hatch in cold, deep waters (> 1,000 m) after which they move up into shallower, warmer waters (400–600 m). The animals are thought to live for 18-20 months.
Carnivore. Assumed to eat small fish and crustaceans.

The living animal is very rarely seen, as it lives in mid-water depths of the open ocean. It is found deeper during the day at 550-1,000 m, but at night rises to feed at about 100-300 m below the surface. Once the animal has died the floating shells travel long distances.

Rather fragile, white, loosely-coiled shell which is the internal buoyance device of a small oceanic squid. The animal is rarely seen. It has a bioluminescent photophore on the tail which gives off a green light and which gives it its other name of tail-light squid.

They vary in size and shape, ranging from 60 mm to 450 mm. This great range of shapes and sizes is partly due to the variation in parapodia, or flaps, on each side of the body. Colours include chocolate, amber, black, or mottled. Two tentacles, often shaped like ears, are visible on the head. They have a small internal shell.
Almost all of the sea hares in this genus carry glands that can secrete a purple ink-like fluid when disturbed. Swimming is achieved in some species by undulation of the parapodia.
Herbivorous. Many of the New Zealand species feed predominantly on red algae.
Sea hares have flaps that are often extravagantly ruffled or curled. They have a large variety of colours.
North Island and northern South Island.

Abundant on mid-tidal mud flats. Grows to 20–25 mm long, but can get up to 29 mm. Brownish or greenish-grey, and often eroded. The inside of the aperture is yellowish to dark brown and highly polished when the animal is alive. Aperture is rounded to almost square, with a simple sharp outer lip and a very short, spout-like anterior canal. On the largest (body) whorl the axial ribs stop at the uppermost of two strong spiral ribs. When alive, the operculum (lid) is flexible and round.
The curved growth lines correspond to old aperture openings.
Deposit feeder. It passes large quantities of fine mud through its gut from which it extracts organic material. Leaves behind a noticeable trail.
Abundant in the protected environments provided by mud flats in harbours and estuaries.
Long narrow spire, with whorls crossed by distinct, axial ribs. Two spiral ribs at the base of the lowermost whorl. The aperture ends in a short canal.
Worldwide in tropical and temperate oceans.
Violet below and much paler above. Grows to 4 cm across. It is broadly conical, thin-shelled, smooth, with a large aperture.

The snails all start off as male and at some stage of their lifecycle change sex to become female. Eggs develop inside the female. The male has no penis and releases specialised sperm bodies which swim to the female to fertilise the eggs. Has free-swimming larvae.
Carnivore. Preys on the by-the-wind-sailor (Velella vellela) and the blue button (Porpita porpita).
Floats at the surface of the ocean on a raft of bubbles which are glued together by mucus.

The violet snail has reverse countershading. Countershading is a form of camouflage where the animal is dark on top and light underneath. Oceanic fish are often countershaded - dark upper bodies blend in with the depths of the ocean when seen from above, and when seen from below lighter bellies give cover against sky. As the violet snail floats upside down beneath its bubble raft, it has a paler top and a darker bottom.
West coast of the North Island.

Yellowish, reddish or purplish brown, may be mottled. Grows to just over 6 cm tall. Shell solid, with a tall, straight-sided conical spire. The whorls have ridges of varying sizes which wind their way up the spire. It is narrower than Maoricolpus roseus roseus (which has 2 thick ridges near the base of the whorls which are lacking in Maoricolpus roseus manukauensis).
Sexes separate. Over summer the females carry eggs in capsules inside the mantle cavity until the larvae are released into the water column. Can live for at least 3 years.
Mudflats and shallow channels in harbours and estuaries on the west coast of the North Island.
Very similar to Maoricolpeus roseus roseus, but narrower and more tightly coiled. Only found in estuaries and harbours on the west coast of the North Island.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Invasive species in south eastern Australia, probably since the 1920s.

Yellowish, reddish or purplish brown, may be mottled. Grows to just over 8.5 cm tall. Shell solid, with a tall, straight-sided conical spire. Has two thick, closely-spaced spiral ridges near the base of the body whorl (last whorl), with the lowest of the 2 outlining the lower edge of the whorl. These wind their way up the spire along with thinner spiral ridges. The outside corner of the aperture is almost square.
Sexes separate. Over summer the females carry eggs in capsules inside the mantle cavity until the larvae are released into the water column. Can live for at least 3 years.
In clean shelly sediments in channels, and on muddy rock platforms amongst coralline algae, in areas with moderate to strong currents, from low water to 130 m water depth.
Very similar to Maoricolpeus roseus manukauensis, but broader and less tightly coiled. Maoricolpeus roseus manukauensis is only found in estuaries and harbours on the west coast of the North Island.
North Island and northwest of South Island, also southern Australia.

Shell moderately large, ovate-cylindrical, may reach 50 mm long and 30 mm wide. Light yellowish-brown colour, densely marbled in reddish-brown. The spire is completely sunken, and the aperture runs the full length of the shell. Has no operculum (lid).
Mostly nocturnal, it buries itself in mud when the tide is out. It is hermaphrodite, and lays spiral strings of eggs inside clear jelly spheres. Dies after breeding.
Intertidal mudflats in sheltered situations, associated with eel-grass.
Bubble-shaped shell, marbled with light and reddish-brown.
North Island, Kermadec Islands, Tasmania, New South Wales to western Australia.

Common in northern New Zealand. Grows to about 25 mm high. Tightly fitting operculum (lid) is granular, and may be pinkish-lilac or orange-tan with two spiral bands of black. Although the shell is uniformly black, in adult shells it can show white at the apex if eroded.

When necessary Nerita can breathe in damp air. Its eggs are deposited under stones or in depressions in tidal pools, clustered in tough capsules forming small greyish-white patches. Nerita occurs in dense congregations or can be widely scattered. Juveniles cluster in crevices or under boulders for shelter.
Scrapes lichens and organic debris off rocks and other surfaces with its strong radula, which is like a ribbon studded with minute teeth.
Abundant in northern parts of New Zealand on rocky upper tidal zone. High to mid intertidal range.
Moderate size, very solid and globose in shape. Smooth except for shallowly cut spiral lines. Black on the outside, with a white aperture which has a narrow black border.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham Islands, and Auckland and Campbell Islands.

Whitish, with 1 or 2 spiral bands of purplish brown. Has a thick yellowish brown periostracum (skin). Grows to 3 cm across. Circular with an off-centre apex. Underneath there is a shelf which extends across nearly half the shell and which has a curved edge.
There is no planktonic stage and it develops directly from an egg into a juvenile slipper limpet. The snails all start off as male and at some stage of their lifecycle change sex to become female.
Intertidal to at least 45 m water depth.
Is similar to Sigapatella tenuis, but this species is smaller and has a central apex.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Grows up to 10 mm high and 20 mm wide. Small, circular to slightly oval, with a low profile. Periostracum (skin) light-brown, thin, densely layered, and with many short spinelets. Bare shell surface with crowded concentric growth lines.

All slipper limpets are protandrous hermaphrodites. This means they start out as male but have the ability during their life cycle to become female - usually when the female in a population dies one of the males will change sex to become female.
Squat, thin, limpet-like spiral shell, with an apex (tip) that is nearly in the middle. It has a plate on the underside that extends part way across the shell.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Also southern Australia.

Pale orangey brown, with 5 spiral bands of reddish brown blotches. Grows to about 10 cm high. Shell solid, rounded, with a weak shoulder angle which has rounded nodules. The outer edge of the aperture is rolled back and smooth and the inner edge is covered by a broad white callus. It has a short anterior canal.
Carnivore. Buried during the day and active during the night. It uses a sulphuric acid secretion and its radula to bore into bivalve or sea urchin prey.
In shallow water in bays and off oceanic sand beaches, but also in soft substrates on the outer shelf to at least 70 m water depth.
Helmet shells are extremely variable in colour, size and shape and different forms have often wrongly been given different species names.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham and Kermadec Islands.

Seldom grows larger than 10 mm. Distinctive bluish-white colour. It is initially a creamy white with a broad blue spiral band, but the colour is less obvious when it is eroded. Abundant on high tide rocks. Aperture is dark purple-brown.
Lives at the extreme high water mark, where salt spray reaches for only a brief period each day.
Feeds on an inconspicuous dark grey lichen found on high tide rocks.
On exposed coasts. At and above high water mark, on rocks where spray hits at high tide.
Very small, sharply conical shell. Bluish white with a broad spiral band of brighter blue.
North, South, Stewart Chatham and Kermadec Islands. Eastern Australia.

Uncommon. Large and solid. Grows up to 100 mm, occasionally to 130 mm or larger. Heavy and strongly shouldered. When alive it has a dense, golden-brown periostracum (skin) with hair-like filaments. Heavy, rounded axial ribs (varices) are crossed by strong spiral cords of unequal width. The grooves between are a dark chestnut. The inner lip of the aperture is covered in smooth callous. The outer lip is fairly thin-edged and crenulate. Aperture and callous white.

Prefers quieter waters of harbours. The height of the spire is shorter for specimens from more exposed coasts than for those from sheltered sites. Egg capsules are massed on the inner surface of a leathery cup-shaped ‘nest’, 60–90 mm in diameter. Has a planktotrophic (living and feeding in the plankton) larva that lives long enough to cross the Tasman Sea.
Carnivorous. Predatory. In Australia it commonly feeds on the sea squirt, cunjevoi.
More common in the north. Low intertidal to 40m. Open to sheltered locations on rocky reefs. Found around boulders and under rock ledges of reefs in proximity of mud-flats.
Golden-brown trumpet shell with varices (thickened ridges). With strong spiral corrugations and often with nodules on the shoulders of the whorls.
Widespread: New Zealand, southern Australia, Japan, South Africa, north African Atlantic, Mediterranean,and European waters.

Handsome, large and heavy. Grows up to 200 mm long. Inside edge of outer lip has regular pattern of striped ridges at right angle to the edge. Shell colour is highly variable and ranges from brown shells marbled with cream, grey, and fawn or buff, to rarer pinkish shells with orange-red to lemon, marbled with brown. The colour of the shell can be partly hidden by encrusting organisms. The animal is orangy yellow with bright orange tentacles. Each tentacle has 2 black rings and an eye at the base.
Most commonly seen in spring when it comes into shallow water to breed.
Carnivorous, it feeds exclusively on sea stars and sea urchins, such as kina. It uses its long proboscis to inject the prey with an immobilising neurotoxin. The prey is then ingested bit by bit .
Low intertidal to 150m. Open localities, on rocky reefs.
Large, heavy trumpet shell with prominent lip and mottled patterning in brown and white. Largest gastropod in New Zealand.

Pinkish to reddish brown, with numerous lighter, wavy longitudinal stripes. Grows to 9 cm high. Shell solid and fairly broad, with a sharp spire. Whorls have angular shoulders which are studded with bluntly pointed tubercles. The aperture is a rich reddy brown inside and bordered by a thick, smooth white callus which extends onto the body whorl (last whorl).

Sexes separate. Breeds throughout the year, the female has a brood pouch in which she incubates several hundred small eggs. These hatch into four-lobed larvae which are then released into the plankton.

Filter feeder. This species lives 5 cm or so below the sediment surface and constructs a mucus-lined channel to draw water from the surface. Food particles are filtered from this water by special filaments on the gills. These particles are transported to the mouth in a continuous mucus string. The spent water is returned to the surface via another channel.
Lives just below the sediment surface on sandy beaches. From low tide to shallow subtidal.
The ostrich foot belongs to a strictly southern group of shells, which are found only in New Zealand, southern and eastern Australia and South Georgia and Kerguelen Island.
North east coast of North Island and eastern Australia.

Large, thin shell, grows to 230 mm high. Has broad, flattened spiral corrugations separated by narrow unsculptured grooves. When alive covered with thin, yellowish periostracum (skin). Shell colour variable from pale cream to bright orange-brown. Often has scattered reddish-brown to purplish-brown blotches near the top and base of the body-whorl. Has a very large aperture with a thin-edged outer lip.

All shells in this group are noted for their large, yet relatively thin shells, rapidly increasing whorls, wide aperture, and the large size of the last whorl when compared to the earlier whorls. They have a long thick tubular proboscis and a broad foot, but no operculum (lid). Occasionally wash ashore on north Auckland beaches.
Carnivorous. Active hunters feeding on burrowing bivalves and echinoderms.
Lives on open sandy bottoms from below low tide to 150 m.
Very large, thin shell, with low spire and very large body (last) whorl sculptured with strong spiral corrugations.

Yellowish brown, irregularly coiled tube which can grow to at least 10 cm. Irregular ridges run the length of the tube and are in turn crossed by irregular ribs that give the tube a scaly texture. The animal is mainly yellowish-brown to chocolate and the foot plug is orange-red, and it cements one side of the tube to hard surfaces.

Eggs are incubated in capsules attached to the inside of the tube. There are about 3-5 capsules with about 10 eggs in each. There is no planktonic larval stage, and when the eggs hatch the young embryo leaves the shell and crawls around for a short time before it attaches itself to a hard surface.
Lives attached to hard substrates, on rocky reefs or under stones. Prefers clean water and some wave surge. From low intertidal to at least 40 m water depth.

As a newly-hatched embryo it has the regularly-coiled shell of a gastropod. However, as it grows the adult shell becomes more and more irregularly-coiled and looks more like a tube worm. It does not have an operculum (lid) but closes the shell with its disc-shaped foot.
North, South, Stewart and the Chatham Islands. Uncommon.

35–80 mm in diameter. Shell is thin with a granular surface texture. The later whorls are concave, but whorls close to the tip are strongly convex. Attractive with its distinctive pattern of brown stripes on a creamy white background. The inside of the aperture is iridescent pink, and the aperture can be closed off with a circular brown operculum (lid).
Little is known about the biology of this species.
Feeds mainly on hydroids, which are encrusting animals related to sea anemones.
Likes clear water. Lives in sheltered shaded positions on rocky substrate, under boulders, on rock walls and under overhangs, below low tide to 200 m. Semi to very exposed open coasts.
Shell is thin and broadly conical. Lower whorls are concave, but convex close to the tip. Conspicuous pattern of chestnut or reddish brown zigzags or broken stripes.
North, South and Stewart Islands. Also Australia.

Usually between 100–200 mm long, it has a shield-shaped shell that is much smaller than the animal itself. The shell has a curved posterior edge and a straight front end, and it is marked with concentric growth rings. This narrow, oblong plate protects the heart and other vital organs. Thin folds of the black mantle often completely hide it from view, although it is sometimes visible through a thin gap between the folds. The body is plump and muscular, with a broad foot that can stick to vertical surfaces.

It occupies a bare scar, the size of its foot, to which the animal returns regularly after feeding trips. It is a common species, but sometimes undetected because it appears to avoid light and mainly feeds at night.
Browses on seaweeds such as neptunes necklace (Hormosira banksii), sea lettuce (Ulva spp.) and bubble algae (Colpomenia spp.).

Found from low intertidal to 20 m depth, on rocky shores and reefs. Often on the underside of boulders, may also be found among subtidal kelp, or on sand or gravel in channels within harbours and estuaries. Can cope with silted reefs.
Large, jet black, and slug-like with thick tentacles at the front.
Northern part of North Island and Chatham Islands.

Not a true limpet, the oval shell is 20-50 mm long, with the body 15-20 mm longer than shell. Mantle skirt extending from under shell is pale grey to dull yellow, with grey-brown streaks and/or scattered spots. Oval shell is smooth and white inside, white-buff or yellowish to brown and criss-crossed with delicate ridges on outside. Edge of shell is crenulated or delicately toothed, with a shallow groove.
Little is known about the biology of this species. It is often found in association with encrusting bryozoans, sponges and ascidians.
Grazes on marine algae and also crustose sponges.
Lives under boulders and in crevices on sheltered to semi-exposed rocky coast. Low intertidal to sublittoral fringe.
Large and limpet-like. The body is larger than the shell and folds back to partly cover the shell.
North, South, Stewart, and Chatham Islands as well as the subantarctic islands.

Large, oval shell with a very small, almost smooth, spire. A large individual may be 160 mm long and 125 wide, more commonly about 115 mm long and 85 mm wide. Outside off-white to dark brown, and adults are often covered with encrusting organisms such as coralline algae. The animal is mainly black but its foot is dark grey. The interior of the shell is brilliantly iridescent in deep peacock blue and green.

Common, but rarer where regularly harvested. As a true gastropod, the animal retains a small visceral spire and is therefore not quite symmetrical. The body whorl has become enormously expanded and the shell spire is so reduced it now has a limpet-like form. The row of holes visible near one margin, are respiratory apertures, through which the animal vents water from the gills. It can crawl quite quickly and clings to flat rock surfaces with great suction.
Grazer. It uses a radula, which is a ribbon-like structure studded with hundreds of tiny hard, sharp teeth, to browse coralline and other algae.

Lower intertidal to 10m. It is found under boulders and ledges, in crevices, and on open rock surfaces on rocky reefs of semi-exposed to exposed coasts. Can form large aggregations. Juveniles are limited to more protected locations such as the underside of boulders.
Large, oval, flattened shell, with a row of holes along the back. Internal opalescent lustre of greens and blues.

Ornate, moderately large and solid. Usually 25-40 mm, but may be up to 55 mm. Shell is strongly sculptured with about 11 prominent white radial ribs, alternating with smaller, dark brown to black riblets which are decorated with a series of white bumps. Older shells are a duller, greyish brown and eroded. Apex is off-centre, at about a third from the margin. Shell margins are strongly scalloped. Interior is dark brown at centre and finely rayed in dark brown on a light-coloured background. The animal is cream to yellow-fawn.

Common. It can reach densities of about 100 per square metre in south eastern New Zealand. It shows strong 'homing' behaviour, returning to its home location after feeding. A breeding study showed individuals are capable of reproducing after their first year on the shore, but that reproductive output increases with size. There is often a single spawning period during summer, which peaks during January to February, although the timing and size of this peak may differ greatly between years and sites.
Grazer. Limpets are among the dominant grazers of many intertidal. shores
Rock surfaces of semi-protected to exposed rocky shores. Ranges from low to high tidal levels. Can tolerate some drying out.
Oval and conical, with either steep or low cone. Prominent radial ribs and decorated with bumps.

Grows to 50 mm long. Thinner, wider and flatter than Cellana ornata, with its apex closer to the margin. 20–25 smooth low radial ribs, may be indistinct or absent in northern forms. Colour is highly variable, ranging from plain silvery-grey to tortoise-shell in yellow and rich reddish-brown, radial streaks may be brown and white. Often a dull greyish-brown with darker radial streaks along the ribs. Southern shells may be uniformly dark grey, with fine radial lines between the ribs. Interior often buff at the centre with dark rays reaching to the margin, sometimes has a uniform silvery lustre.

Our most common limpet. It can make long grazing forages of more than 1 m, especially at night and during high tides. Can aggregate in and around damp rock depressions. May become encrusted with barnacles, or algae.
Grazes among barnacles and within cleared patches on the coralline turf or on smooth coralline paint.
Mid to low intertidal on rocky shores.
Oval, low profile cone with the apex off-set from the middle and close to the margin. Smooth, low radial ribs.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham, and Kermadec Islands.

Very beautiful tall shell, growing to 45 mm high. A broadly rounded outline and an almost smooth surface, except for linear spiral grooves on the upper whorls and a few on the lower base. Also has faint axial growth lines. Zig-zag stripes on white or cream background, stripes gradually change in colour from russet or orange on the early higher whorls to mauve below. Inside surface of the aperture opalescent, giving the shell its species name of opalus.
Lives on the fronds of kelp at and below low tide. Not commonly seen. Little is known about the biology of this species.
Subtidal edge down to at least 15 m on open rocky coasts.

Pointed top-shell with delicate zig-zags on a whitish background. Zig-zag colours orange near to the tip of the spire gradually changing to mauve on the body (last) whorl. Opalescent inside the aperture.

Variable in colour, from greenish grey to bright rose. Grows to 3 cm high. Conical, with spiral grooves crossed by oblique lines which give the grooves a pitted appearance. The inside of the aperture is an iridescent pink.
Has a broad foot which helps it stick to kelp fronds in areas with strong surge.
Grazer on brown seaweeds, especially Ecklonia kelp.
From low tide to 50 m water depth, on open rocky shores.
Smaller than the opal top shell, and with a more coarsely textured surface.

White, patterned with reddish to chocolate brown rectangles. Grows to 1.4 cm high. The shell is a low cone, with slightly convex sides, and patterned with regularly spaced beaded cords. The underside has a large hole through the centre of the cone. The aperture is an iridescent white.
Grazer on seaweed, and a deposit feeder in tidal channels.
Low intertidal to about 45 m water depth. On rocks amongst kelp holdfasts (attachments), sponges and seasquirts, usually in more protected environments.
It has a lower spire than Coelotrochus viridis and a less nodular texture.

Greenish grey or dull purplish. Grows to 2.5 cm high. A solid, tall cone with spiral rows of nodules and a flat base. Underneath there is a hole through the centre of the cone, and the flat base has regularly-spaced reddish spiral lines.
Has a broad foot which helps it stick to kelp fronds and hard surfaces in areas with strong surge.
Grazer on brown seaweeds and pink coralline crust.
Mostly found below low tide, on the blades of Ecklonia kelps. Juveniles also on pink coralline crusts.
It is taller than Coelotrochus tiaratus and has a coarser, more nodular texture.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Common. It is 21-28 mm high, 21-31 mm wide. Unweathered specimens are covered by a dull greenish-brown periostracum (skin) with distinct spiral grooves on the surface. Weathered specimens are dark blue, purplish-brown, to black with spiral lines of long white dashes. Especially worn specimens may be a dull grey on the spire. The black outer lip has a sharp edge.
One of the most abundant species on coastal rocks. Adults can be seen on open surfaces and boulders. Juveniles are concealed in crevices, among algae or underneath boulders.
Herbivorous, grazes on algal film and small algae on rocks.
High to low intertidal. Sheltered to semi-exposed rocky coasts.
Globular shell with a flat to shallow spire, dominated by a plump lower whorl. Easily recognised by the spiral lines of white dashes on a dull purplish black background.

Mostly a dull purplish brown zigzag pattern on a light yellowish background, but patterning and colour varies. However, all have a bright yellow margin along the outer lip, which may be broken up by dark blotches. Grows to just over 3 cm high. Solid, rounded cone, with a few strong spiral ridges. Older eroded shells may be nearly smooth. The base and the inside of the aperture are pearly white.
Broad-cast spawner which releases eggs and sperm into the plankton, and has planktonic larvae.
Lives on mudflats in estuaries and harbours. Lives at about the mid-tide level and can tolerate brackish conditions.

There are 7 other Diloma species of top shells in New Zealand, and they all occur in the intertidal zone. Diloma subcarinata is the only one that lives on mudflats and the only one that has a yellow margin to the aperture.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Creamy white or pinkish, with a radial pattern of purply or reddish brown zigzags. Grows to just over 2 cm across. Solid, low-spired, smooth with a silky sheen. The lower surface of the shell has a heavy callus at its centre which is bordered by a wide purple band. The inside of the aperture is a light iridescent green.
Filter feeder. Specialised filaments on the gills trap food particles which are carried to the mouth by a continuous mucus string.
Low intertidal to shallow subtidal, in clean, fine sand of channels and ocean beaches.
This species can be very numerous on open sand beaches, and in some places lives at densities of 3500 per square metre.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Greyish to reddish brown. Grows to 12 cm across. Low-spired with a concave base which has a hole through the centre. Distinctive circular outline with large saw-tooth spines along the margin of the shell.
Grazer. Grazes on calcareous and microscopic algae.
In rocky, exposed to semi-exposed, locations, from low intertidal to 120 m water depth.

It is a member of the Turbinidae family which can be recognised by their heavy calcareous operculum (lid). Other members of this family are Cook's turban (Cookia sulcata) and the cat's eye (Lunella smaragdus), both of which have a calcareous operculum.

Fairly common. Heavy and broadly conical, 65–80 mm high. Outside surface is layered, dull grey to pinky fawn when alive. Strong oblique ridges are crossed by fine lamellar growth lines. The interior and the area around the aperture are smooth and pearly. The operculum (lid) is a shelly oblong plate with several spiral ridges. The outer lip is jagged.

May live up to 8–10 years, but is mature at 20 mm high. Its reproductive season is December to February. This species can have a significant grazing impact on foliose red algae and is part of a complex grazing ecology. For example, when it removes foliose macro-algae it may allow smaller grazers such as the limpet Cellana to move into these sub-tidal zones.
Juveniles feed on the brown algae of the sublittoral fringe and may be seen on stipes (stems) and blades of kelp. Adults feed on small foliose or turfing coralline algae.
Solely subtidal. Found under stones, rocky ledges and in crevices of rock surfaces along semi-exposed to exposed coasts. Found down to approximately 20 m.
Large and turban-shaped. Oblique ridges are crossed by fine laminae. Often encrusted by calcareous algae.

One of our best known intertidal shells. 40-70 mm high, 50-73 wide. Large and solid, with evenly convex smooth whorls in the adult. Juveniles have sharp spiral ridges. Colour greenish-black. Aperture and callous silver-white and slightly iridescent. The cats-eye door, the operculum, is pale bluish-green with a callused white area. The animal is black with a white sole to the foot.

A dominant organism of the seaweed zone of the intertidal. There is size sorting, with the largest animals living at the lowest tide levels. Wave action dislodges individuals when they grow to a critical size, and rolls them down the shore to areas where there is less disturbance by waves.
Herbivorous. Feeds on seaweeds and coralline algae.
Wide range of intertidal and shallow subtidal habitats.
Dark shell, with rounded whorls, especially the body (last) whorl. The greenish operculum (lid) of the living animal is what gives it the common name of cat's eye.
North, South and Three Kings Islands. First example was noted in Auckland Harbour.

One of our most frequently encountered nudibranchs. 50–70 mm long. Common in northern waters. Usually uniformly yellow, but colours can range from lemon-yellow, deep chrome, orange-brown, rusty-red to transluscent white. Has a scattering of small white specks over the mantle. The rhinophores (chemical sensors), which look similar to fleshy antennae, may be a shade darker than the mantle, and have pale to white tips.

The rhinophores are used to detect chemicals dissolved in the surrounding sea water. It lacks radula, oral tentacles or jaws, but it has an extendible proboscis which glides out of a small mouth pore. It uses this to pierce its ascidian prey and to inject enzymes that digest the ascidian’s tissues. A capillary-like oesophagus then serves as a muscular pump to suck up pre-digested food. If left high and dry by the receding tide it can survive and recover when the tide returns.
Generally mid to low intertidal. Found in a great range of habitats, from open coasts to silted harbours. May be found crawling on coralline weed in algae fringed rock pools, and on wharf piles.
Brightly coloured, usually yellow, and slug-like, with fleshy rhinophores (antenna-like organs of smell) at one end and a feathery gill at the other. Nudibranch means naked gill.
North Island, north west coast of South Island, east coast to Timaru, Chatham Islands.

Colour and stripes are variable. Shallow vertical sculpture on early whorls, but later whorls usually smooth. The large body whorl takes up at least half the total height of the shell. The aperture is ovate, and ends in a short anterior canal.
Common. Regularly encountered in faunal surveys at a range of depths.
Carnivorous and also scavenges for dead remains.
Under ledges and rocks on sheltered to open coasts. Intertidal to at least 100 m.
Spiral shell tapering at both ends, smooth rounded whorls with brown spiral stripes on a yellowish background
North Island, northern part of South Island and Chatham Islands.

Grows to 50 mm high. Whorls roundly to massively shouldered. Some individuals have spiral grooves but others are smooth. Colour varies from uniformly chocolate-brown to spiral rows of reddish-brown squarish dots on a buff or yellowish-brown background. In living animals the operculum (lid) is leaf-shaped, thick and dark brown. Abundant in the North Island.
Groups may be seen feeding together on prey. Females aggregate to lay eggs at the base of rocky formations.

Carnivorous. Cominella is an active hunter of prey such as the cockle, Austrovenus stutchburyi, and may also opportunistically scavenge. Lab research shows they preferentially attacked small cockles. However, large size does not necessarily protect such prey from predation by Cominella.
Most often found where rocky ground is close to mudflats, in sheltered harbours and semi-sheltered locations. Mid-intertidal to at least 20m.
Shell solid. Spire height, sculpturing and colour pattern all vary within populations. Interior of aperture is chrome or orange-yellow.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Dull greenish grey or brown, often coated in mud. Grows to 2.5 cm high. Shell ovate, fairly solid, with a wide smooth concave slope above the shoulder and with nodules on the shoulder itself. The aperture is half the total height of the shell, and brown inside with a bright purple margin. The operculum (lid) is dark brown.

Lays 6-7 eggs on the insides of empty cockle shells in conical orange capsules. The mud whelk is a direct developer which means it does not have a planktonic larva and hatches directly into tiny crawling individual. Only a few of the eggs develop into small snails and the rest act as nurse cells.
Carnivore. Preys on cockles and other bivalves and scavenges for dead or dying organisms. It uses its siphon to 'taste' the water for prey.
On intertidal mudflats and sandflats in sheltered waters.
North Island and northern part of the South Island.

Pale greenish yellow with a spiral pattern of dark brown rectangular spots. Grows to 4.5 cm high. Shell elongate-ovate, almost smooth, but often badly eroded. Aperture is bluish grey to purplish brown.

Lays 4-12 eggs inside an oval egg capsule which is attached to the substrate by a short stalk. Eggs hatch after 9-10 weeks and, like the mud whelk, the spotted whelk does not have a planktonic larval stage, but develops directly into a tiny crawling individual.
Carnivore. Scavenges for dead or dying organisms. It uses its siphon to 'taste' the water for prey.
The dark brown rectangular spots, or 'maculae', give this shell its species name of 'maculosa', which means spotted.
Northern North Island to Mahia Peninsula and Ahipara on west coast.

Common intertidal. Height 30–42 mm, width 15–20 mm. Colour ranges from ash grey to yellowish with bright orange around the aperture, and a purplish-brown interior. Has a short anterior canal. Shells south of Whangarei can be solid, almost smooth, but with weak axial ribs over the early whorls, 6-7 regular dark brown spiral lines on the body whorl. A second form found on the west coast from Ahipara north, and east coast north of Whangarei has stronger axial ribs and more numerous, but weaker spiral lines.

Females lay eggs in communal groups. Egg capsules, which contain a single embryo, are attached underneath boulders or in rocky crevices. When first hatched juveniles are only 3 mm. In the first 2 months they are vulnerable to predation or crushing by predators such as medium and large sized shore crabs.
Carnivorous and scavenging. Feeds on top-shells, cats-eyes or scavenges for dead animals. Eats by inserting the long eversible proboscis into the tissues.
Beneath rocks and stones on the mid to low intertidal rocky shore. Also on Corallina-Hormosira flats, in tide pools or in moist depressions.

Slender. Tall spire and a narrow body-whorl which has 6-7 thin dark brown spiral lines for east coast subspecies south of Whangarei; shells further north and on west coast more stunted and with more than twice the number of spiral lines.

Large, solid, spindle-shaped with a long canal. Generally up to 100 mm but capable of reaching 160 mm. Variable in colour and shape, but consistently has strong spiral cords or threads which wind up the spire. Colour ranges from yellowish-grey through to dark brown, and may be marbled with reddish-brown. Aperture is white and edged with brown crenulations patterned with white strips. Whorls may be angled and squarely shouldered and knobbed, or smooth and rounded. The operculum (lid) that blocks the aperture is teardrop-shaped, thick and brown.

A predator, it feeds by extending its long probosis into bivalve prey such as the venus shell. The long canal is a feature of many carnivorous or scavenging marine snails and houses the siphon. This tube-like structure has chemical sensors which are used to taste the water for prey. Little is known about its breeding biology.
Carnivorous. Feeds on a wide range of prey, including shallowly burrowing bivalves.
Low intertidal to 100 m. Rocky reefs at low tide.
Solid, spindle-shaped shell. Strong spiral threads run around the shell.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Yellowish white with reddish brown longitudinal streaks. Shallow water shells have a thin, pale periostracum (skin), whereas those from deep water have a thick, dark periostracum. Grows to 7.5 cm high. The shoulder has a strong spiral keel studded with white nodules or tubercles.
On fine sand or silty mud, from low tide to over 500 m water depth.
Looks like the ostrich foot shell, Struthiolaria papulosa, but in the knobbed whelk the outside edge of the aperture is always very thin, whereas in the ostrich foot it is thickened.

Common, 55 mm long, with large individuals reaching 65 mm long and 45 mm wide. Outside is dull purplish-black or dark grey-brown. Spiral grooves may be eroded. The lip of the large aperture is thin and crenulated. Interior is dirty white with a conspicuous dark brown or purple pattern near the outer lip, which is rimmed with white. When alive, the operculum (lid) is dark brown.

An active hunter, it will attack other molluscs. It has been known to force open oysters and other bivalves by inserting the lip of its own shell as a wedge, but also bores holes into shells. More than one Haustrum can sometimes be seen preying on the same individual.
Carnivorous. Preys on a wide range of other molluscs, including top shells and oysters.
Mid to low intertidal. Common on rocky ground in sheltered to moderately exposed locations where it is found in crevices, under ledges and boulders.
Large, solid, with a low conical spire and a large and rounded body (lower) whorl that tapers gradually. Weak external spiral grooves. Large aperture.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Shell often eroded or encrusted. Small, generally up to 25 mm high, though sometimes larger. A single ridge winds around the spire and 3 ridges wind around the body whorl. Surface texture rough and sometimes nodular. The aperture is small, and the edge is thin and crenulated. Colour pale greyish or buff with a speckled spiral pattern in dark brown. Inside it is purplish-brown.

Plays havoc on rock oyster beds. Uses its radula (teeth) and chemical action to drill holes through the oyster's shell, which may take as much as 45 minutes. It then uses its proboscis to inject digestive enzymes.
Carnivorous. Prey includes oysters and mussels.
Mid intertidal rocky reefs in sheltered to open locations.
Small, solid, spiral shell with prominent shoulders and a few strong spiral ridges.
North Island west coast, from Ahipara to Kawhia.

Whitish. Grows to almost 2 cm high. The spire has a keel with large nodules, which disappears as the shell grows. The body whorl (last whorl) has 4 deep spiral grooves. The aperture is purplish inside and there is a row of blunt 'teeth' just inside the outer lip.
This species is characteristic of Auckland's exposed west coast.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.
