Yellowish white. Grows to just over 7 cm high. Has a tall spire, but shape and sculpture differs between female and male shells. Female shells are larger and more strongly ornamented with a lattice of ridges and spines. Males are smaller and much less sculptured.
Sexes separate. The female lays her eggs on the back of the male's shell as well as other empty mollusc shells. Has planktonic larvae.
On sand or mud, from low tide to 90 m water depth.
One of the few molluscs where the shape of the shell differs between sexes.
North Island and northern part of South Island.

Handsome, smooth and polished shell up to 30 mm long and occasionally to 40 mm length. Elongate oval shape with a broad spire. Distinctively coloured; a wide central band of hazy bluish brown on dark or reddish brown. A white spiral line borders the top of the broad body whorl. This is partially hidden above the aperture by a white callous. In live animals the operculum (lid) is golden yellow, thin and only half the size of the aperture.

The soft part of the animal inside the shell is white and speckled with grey. When it is foraging the mantle almost totally encloses the shell, leaving only the back and spire visible. Burrows just below the surface leaving an obvious trail. Usually has the siphon extended above the sediment surface.
Sandy flats. Lives among fronds of kelp at and below low tide down to 10 m.
Solid, oval, almost bullet-shaped shell, broad bluish-slate grey spiral and dark brown above and below.

Pinkish or pale yellowish, with a spiral pattern of zigzags. Grows to around 13 cm high. Solid and elongate, with a very long aperture which has 4-6 pleats on the inside lip and a large broad callus that extends onto the body whorl (last whorl). Sculpture varies, and shells from high-energy environments are smooth, but those from more sheltered environments have pointed tubercles on the shoulder.
Sexes separate, the female lays eggs in large calcareous cases which she cements onto dead shells (pictured). Up to 3 baby Alcithoe hatch from each case and there is no planktonic stage.
Carnivore. Lives in the sediment during the day and comes out at night to hunt bivalve molluscs.
Lives buried in the sediment in a variety of habitats, from sheltered estuaries to open coasts, intertidal to about 70 m water depth.
Rarely seen alive, but often found as eroded, damaged shells (pictured).
North, South and Stewart Islands, south eastern Australia.

Grows to around 100 mm. The soft body is finely textured with small folds. It has no shell. Colours can range from cream to brown with a mottled colour pattern. The rhinophores (chemical sensors) are located on the sides of the head. The wide oral veil at the front is straight and shovel-shaped. The mantle is smaller than the foot. It is most often seen on beaches in spring, when onshore winds can wash it up onto the tide line.

Deadly toxic when eaten. Responsible for the first ever tetrodotoxin poisonings in New Zealand when several dogs were poisoned in 2009. A single adult slug may contain enough toxin to kill several adult humans. As even the mucous and egg strings can be toxic care should be taken to keep children and dogs from coming into contact. Specimens in Auckland Museum’s collections, dating from 1994, also contained tetrodotoxin. Therefore it is likely to have always been toxic and not a recent occurrence. For more information use an internet key word search: toxic sea slug Auckland Museum.

Opportunistic carnivore. Active forager, and particularly eats sea anemones, but will eat a wide range of smaller invertebrates, including dead or dying ones. Sea slugs in this genus can be cannibalistic.
Wide range of habitats, from silty harbours to open rocky coasts. Low intertidal to 250 m.

DEADLY TOXIC when eaten. Even the mucous and egg string can be very toxic. Has a straight, shovel-shaped front and two prominent rhinophores (chemical sensors) sticking out on the sides of the head. The mantle is slightly smaller than the foot and a feathery gill is tucked under the mantle on the right side of the animal.
North, South, Stewart, and Chatham Islands.

40-70 mm. Internal shell 12-20 mm. Varying from milky white to pale buff with scattered reddish-brown blotches. Internal shell-remnant rectangular, thin, semi-transparent and slightly iridescent. Mantle is smooth and soft to the touch. Rhinophores (chemical sensors) at the front are chocolate-brown with pale tips. The long gill is tucked under the mantle on the right side. The gill and foot are white.
It is capable of discharging a thick, milky irritant from the mantle surface for protection.
Low intertidal to 6 m. Rocky reefs, under stones, in semi-sheltered to open locations.
Pale brown to reddish brown sea slug with red-brown spots over the mantle.

Yellowish brown, but usually covered in mud. Grows to 3 cm. Shell rounded, but with a ridge on the shoulder. Has a low spire, the surface is coarsely wrinkled and the aperture is crescent-shaped and a reddy brown inside.
Hermaphrodite, but exchanges sperm. Lays a sticky open-ended coil of eggs and mud (pictured), which may contain more than 10,000 eggs.
Eats large quantities of mud from which it extracts microscopic algae and bacteria. The sifted mud particles are passed out as a continuous faecal string.
Occurs in large numbers on mudflats in the high intertidal. When the tide is in it hides in the mud to avoid being eaten by fish.
Around Auckland it is often found in large numbers amongst mangrove roots.
North, South and Chatham Islands. Also known from southeast of Australia.

Usually up to 20 mm, but may reach 30 mm. The leathery back is generally granular, sometimes with tiny knobbles, but can be smooth. Colour usually black or dark grey, but sometimes patterned with mottled colours, ranging from brown to orange-red, or yellowish-green. It has 16-20 marginal glands.

Common to abundant. It has lungs and is an air-breather, so is more like a land snail than a sea slug. It has glands that can secrete a protective noxious fluid to discourage predators. It has a free swimming larval stage.
Predominantly a herbivore. Consumes a variety of micro- and macro-algae. Small zooplankton may also be ingested when present.
Mid to low intertidal, where it is found in proximity to mud. May be found on boulders, in crevices or in pools.
Looks like a limpet without its shell. Round to oval, with a broad, low keel.
Throughout the Waitemata Harbour, presently spreading south into the Firth of Thames. Also Whangarei Harbour. Native to eastern, southern and western Australia.

Reddish brown, with dark brown bands at the top and bottom of the body whorl (last whorl). Grows to 12 mm high. Robust, almost bullet-shaped, with longitudinal ribs which have white nodules at their tops. The aperture is bordered by a thick white callus and the thick outer lip has a series of 'teeth' along the inner edge. The hind end of the foot has two sensory tentacles.
Probably has a planktonic larval stage.
Carnivore. Scavenges and preys on dead or dying organisms. It uses its siphon to 'taste' the water for prey.
On sand and mud in estuaries and sheltered locations, intertidal.
Introduced, first found in the Waitemata Harbour in mid-2009.
A small, opportunistic scavenger which, for its size, moves very rapidly and which uses its long flexible siphon to 'taste' the water for prey.
North, South, Stewart and Auckland Islands.

Up to 25 mm. Narrow and elongated. The girdle bears tufts of long bristles, sprouting from the sutural pores. The eight dorsal valves (shell plates) are wedge-shaped. Colour variable, girdle and shell often pale brown, but may be dark brown and white, with irregular blotches.
Tends to live among large algae but will tolerate muddy conditions.
Intertidal to shallow subtidal. Common under stones and overhangs, and among foliose algae in rock pools.
Small, narrow, elongate and oval. Tufts of long bristles on the girdle.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

60–70 mm long. Has a rubbery girdle which almost completely hide the eight valves (shell plates). Colour can vary and includes brown, orange, and green. It may be uniform in colour or variegated. Valves are pale blue or white, but buried in the girdle.

All chitons graze with a radula, which is a narrow ribbon covered in strong teeth. Spawning observed in Otago followed a lunar periodicity that corresponded with the five sets of spring tides during 8-9 weeks in winter. Eggs are laid in long gelatinous strings.

Appears to be more or less omnivorous. Grazes on plants, but also eats organisms such as byozoans, and at Leigh Marine Reserve it is likely to be one of the most important predators of bryozoans. Individuals dissected from this location had only bryozoan fragments in their guts.
Very low intertidal to at least 30 m depth. Often assocated with sponges in deeper water and among seaweeds in low intertidal and subtidal.
Large and fleshy. Short bristles protrude slightly from two rows of blunt, raised pores, and a central row of slits runs along its length.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Also occurs in Tasmania, but may have been accidentally introduced from New Zealand.

Generally 30-35 mm long. Fine lines may be visible on the eight valve (shell plate) surfaces, particularly at the ends. The girdle scales are smooth. Colour usually dark green, but can vary through brown, to light blue. Sometimes patterned with chevrons or zigzag markings.
Feeds and moves around at night and is hidden during the day. The eight moveable plates allow it to roll up for protection.
Grazes on organic debris and algal film.
Intertidal and shallow subtidal. Ranges from open coast to estuarine habitats.
Oval, eight valves (shell plates) surrounded by a narrow girdle with large scales, high arched to a distinct ridge.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands, Tasmania and eastern Australia.

35–40 mm long. The eight movable valves (shell plates) are surrounding by leathery girdle which is studded with scales. The end valves and the tips of the central valves are sculptured with radiating ribs. However, larger animals may be disguised by encrusting algae, or may be eroded. Among the commonest and most widespread of our shore molluscs.

Spends most of its time fastened to rocks by suction. Most adults eventually permanently have elongate depressions or ‘homes’ in the substrate to which they return. It can occur in high densities and counts as high as 228 indviduals per square metre have been recorded. The smallest animals are generally restricted to the lower shore in pools or on areas of rock which are slow to drain. It has to cope with large temperature and salinity changes, and it can live for at least 24 hours in aerated sea water at 30°C.
Herbivorous. Grazing generalist, for example eats coralline algal turf.
Found on a wide range of shore levels but peaks on rock in the mid-intertidal. Occurs mainly on rock surfaces rather than under stones and appears associated with rocks 15–25 cm diameter or larger.
Oval, flattened, mottled brown to olive-green. The girdle around its eight valves (shell plates) has large, snake-like scales.
North, South, Stewart, Snares and Chatham Islands.

Up to 55 mm. Has eight almost smooth and shining valves (shell plates) which may be yellowish to bright green, ornamented with concentric darker lines, or bolder patterns in dark green or reddish-brown, often with wedge-shaped marking down the crest of the valves. The fleshy girdle is velvety and often pink to lilac or green. North Island specimens are sometimes banded. In the South Island, shells are uniformly brown and the girdle is a lighter brown.

Common. Broods its eggs under the mantle. Egg numbers can vary from several hundred to several thousand. Embryos are released after 12–15 days as well-developed larvae. These have some swimming ability, but will settle within hours of hatching.
Low intertidal to 20 m. Underside of boulders and sediment edge of rocky reefs.
Oval, eight valves (shell plates) are smooth, surrounded by a board and fleshy girdle. Colour variable.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Variable colour, but mostly light green or brownish, mottled or streaked in darker green or brown. Sometimes the shell plates are tipped with white, and others are a uniform greenish, orange or orangey brown. Grows to 5 cm long. Elongate oval, it has 8 valves (shell plates), with the tail valve the largest. The leathery girdle has minute scales.
Grazer. Comes out at night to graze on the upper surfaces of rocks.
Common under stones in the intertidal, on sheltered to semi-exposed shores.
Does not like light, and for a chiton it can move very rapidly and will quickly crawl to the underside of a stone after it has been overturned.
North, South, Stewart, Kermadec, and Chatham Islands.

Our largest chiton, up to 110 mm. Shell very large, solid, elongate-ovate. It is extremely flattened in juveniles. The eight valves (shell plates) meet without gaps, and the girdle is wide, leathery, and covered in scattered, short dark bristles. Colour of shell and girdle dark olive-brown often pinkish towards summit of the valves. Interior is dull white. Juveniles are brightly coloured and heavily mottled.
Adults can be eroded and whitish, may also be encrusted.
Low intertidal to 30 m. Found on exposed coastal rock surfaces, within kelp beds or rock surfaces.
Large, solid chiton with wide leathery girdle with short, scattered bristles.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham, Auckland and Campbell Islands.

Yellowish white, younger shells often have an intricate pattern of brown zigzag lines. The shell's inside is a polished white with a violet posterior muscle scar. Grows to 7 cm long. Solid, oblong with the beak (apex) much closer to the anterior end then the posterior end, and with concentric ribs on the outside surface of the shell.
Lives buried 4-7 cm below the surface, in moderately sheltered locations in both muddy and sandy sediments. Shallow subtidal.
Endemic in New zealand, but invasive in eastern Tasmania.
Is an introduced species in Tasmania where it is known as the 'New Zealand venus' or the 'Venus clam'.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Ivory white, with a thin olive brown periostracum (skin), which has usually worn off. Grows to nearly 7 cm long. Shell fairly thin, wedge-shaped, with a straight slope to the posterior end, and a broadly rounded anterior edge.
Sexes are separate. Spawning varies with seasonal factors, such as water temperature, but generally from late spring to late summer.

Surface deposit feeder. At low tide the long siphons extend to the surface and the inhalant siphon sucks up the concentrated plankton soup that is left behind on the sediment surface. The feeding tracks created by the siphons look like bird foot prints (pictured).
Lives up to 20 cm below the sediment surface in harbours and estuaries, from mid-tide to about 5 m water depth.

The wedge shell prefers to live in sandier sediment and does not like mud content over 75%. It is also sensitive to pollutants such as copper and is therefore used by some regional councils as one of the indicator species to help assess the health of estuaries.
Northern half of the North Island. To Taranaki on the west coast and possibly East Cape on the east coast. Also eastern Australia.
Pale back and body with bright orange patches which vary in size and shape, the gills and rhinophores (tentacles on the head for sensing distant chemicals) are magenta in colour. Grows to 6 cm.

Like many nudibranchs the clown nudibranch is a simultaneous hermaphrodite. This means it has both male and female reproductive organs. Individuals exchange sperm after which both animals will lay several batches of fertilised eggs.
Most common subtidally on open rocky shores, sometimes in semi-protected locations. Intertidal to 40 m water depth.
The bright colours of this species are an advertisement to predators not to eat it. It stores distasteful chemicals, which it harvests from the sponges it eats, in glands on its back.
Northern North Island, widespread in the Indo-Pacific region.

The mantle is a tan brown with cream streaked folds and tubercles. The smooth areas between have diamond-shaped brown patches edged and spotted in peacock blue. The large finely-branched gills are edged in black and the rhinophores (tentacles on the head for sensing distant chemicals) are brown. Grows to 7 cm.
Carnivore. Feeds on encrusting sponges. It does not have jaws or a radula. Instead it covers its prey in digestive enzymes and sucks up the softened sponge.
Semi-sheltered coasts, often out in the open in pools and on shore platforms, intertidal to low subtidal.
Has a very variable colour pattern throughout its range within the Indo-Pacific region.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham Islands, also eastern Australia including Victoria and Tasmania.

Yellowish orange to dark khaki on the upper side while the foot and rhinophores (tentacles on the head for sensing distant chemicals) are bright orange. Grows to 20 cm long. Covered with round to flattened pustules, which are largest on the back and smallest on the mantle edge. Although the body is firm and fleshy, it is slimy to the touch.

Spawns over summer. It is a simultaneous hermaphrodite. This means it has both male and female reproductive organs. Individuals exchange sperm after which both animals will lay fertilised eggs. Spawn is salmon-pink, and laid in a wide, spiral ribbon. One large spawn coil was measured at 2.7 m long, and was estimated to contain some 40 million eggs. However it is unknown how many of these eggs hatched.
Carnivore. Rasp feeder on encrusting sponges.
On rocky surfaces on semi-sheltered to exposed areas, intertidal to 20 m.
Our largest nudibranch, which grows to the size of a rugby ball.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Cream mantle, chocolate colouring on the back in bands and streaks. Amounts and patterning of chocolate vary between individuals from almost white to almost completely chocolate. Gills and rhinophores (tentacles on the head for sensing distant chemicals) are brown edged with yellow. Grows to 7 cm. The body is elongate and smooth.
Spawns from November to January. One individual in captivity layed a single coiled string 70 cm long, which contained some 3 million eggs. It is not known how many eggs hatched.
Open and semi-sheltered rocky shores, intertidal to 40 m water depth.
Feels smooth and slippery to the touch.

Velvety black, with 2 translucent grey areas on each side of the head, and a bluish sheen on the head and the edges. Grows up to 3 cm. Elongate, cylindrical, with a blunt, slightly convex head shield. It has a small, curved, fragile internal shell which is completely hidden by the posterior shield.
Probably spawns from winter to spring. The clear gelatinous egg masses are often found in rock pools.
Carnivore. Feeds on marine worms which it sucks up whole.
On coralline algae, but also in silty patches, intertidal to 40 m water depth.
Usually covered in sand grains which stick to the mucus that coats the body. This helps to camouflage the animal, but the mucus also helps it to crawl.
North Island, northern South Island, Chatham Islands. Also southeastern and southwestern Australia and Norfolk Island.

Creamy white to grey brown, grows to just over 10 cm high. A large strong shell, with a low spire and a large aperture. Surface ornament is very variable for this species, ranging from individuals that are nearly smooth to those that have strong spiral ridges with deep grooves.

Adults congregate to spawn, laying eggs in a honey-comb pattern of straight-sided capsules (pictured), often near green-lipped mussels which is one of their prey-species. Has planktonic larvae and can live for nearly 2 decades.
Carnivore. Preys on barnacles and other molluscs.
On rocks on sheltered to exposed coasts, intertidal to below low tide.
Shells on the east coast are often creamy white and squat, whereas those from the west coast are greyish brown and more elongate.
North Island, to Kapiti on the west coast and to Mahia Peninsula on the east coast.
Light to dark brown, grows to 6 cm high. A strong shell with a high spire. Curved spines come off eight varices (longitudinal ridges).

Carnivore. Preys on barnacles and other molluscs. It uses the radula (ribbon with teeth) to bore a perfectly round hole through the shell of its prey species, after which it uses the proboscis to extract the flesh.
On rocky and sandy coasts, from low intertidal to 500 m water depth.
Shells from shallow water have shorter spines, whereas those from deeper water usually have much longer spines .
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Also in eastern and southern Australia, including Tasmania.

A white outer layer beneath and a thin yellowish periostracum (skin), with a pearly layer inside. Grows to almost 10 cm long. Shell large, thin and elongate. The right valve is convex and the left valve is almost flat. When the valves are together there is a gap at one end for the siphons. The beak (apex) is almost central and has a spoon-shaped projection below it.
Lives buried elbow-deep in fine sand or sandy mud from low spring tide to about 200 m water depth. The siphons make two distinct holes on the surface of the sand, about 4 cm apart.
It lives deeply buried in the sediment and is usually only seen as dead shells on the beach.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.
Pure white. Grows to just over 4 cm across. Almost circular in outline, with the beak (apex) central. Has a distinctive chevron sculpture which is not quite symmetrical but slightly off-centre.
Lives in fine sand, in shallow water to about 200m water depth, but most often in less than 10 m off sandy beaches. Usually only seen as dead shells on the beach.
The only shell with a diverging pattern of ridges on the surface of the shell, which helps it to burrow into sediment.
Whitish or yellowish with a reddish brown or dark brown zigzag pattern. Grows to just over 1 cm high. Small and broadly conical, with a concave base.
Low intertidal to shallow subtidal, on rock on semi-exposed to exposed coasts.

Typically found in the same high-energy environments as species of Durvillaea (bull kelp). The concave base of the shell allows the animal to suck onto hard surfaces and to cope with strong wave action.
North Island and northern parts of the South Island.

Light brown, plain or with one or more dark brown spiral bands. Oval, somewhat bullet-shaped with two sharp folds inside the inner edge of the aperture. The top one of these lines up with a ridge that winds around the outside at the base of the shell.
At the start of summer lays spawn masses under rotten logs and boulders. These are covered by zigzag faecal strings, probably to protect the eggs from being eaten by other animals.
High intertidal mudflats, behind mangroves, under salt marsh plants such as glasswort and rushes.
It gets its common name because the upside down outline and folds of the aperture mimic the shape of the human ear.
North, South, Stewart, Chatham Islands, also Auckland and Campbell Islands.

Olive to light brown, iridescent silver inside the valves. Grows to 8 mm across. Shell is a small rounded triangle, with fine concentric ridges on the outside surface. On the inside dorsal edge (the edge where the valves hinge) there is a long row of comb-like teeth on either side of the beak (apex). There is often a crust of dark-stained sediment around the apex of the shell.
Surface deposit feeder. Does not have siphons and instead sorts organic particles from the sediment with specialised 'lips' that are found on each side of the mouth.
Common on sea-grass flats, but also muddy sand or sandy mud, can occur at densities of 100s per square metre, intertidal to 20 m water depth.

The nut shell prefers to live in sandier sediment and does not like mud content over 60%. It is also sensitive to organic enrichment and copper contamination and is therefore used by some regional councils as one of the indicator species to help assess the health of estuaries.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Creamy white on the outside, but inside each valve there is a purplish brown patch at the posterior end of the shell. Grows to 4.5 cm length. Moderately large, solid, ovate and inflated. The hinge, where the valves join, is almost straight. The outside surface has a radial pattern of ribs which are strongest at posterior end of the shell, and with the ones closest to the front edge (below the beak) patterned with a second set of raised riblets at right angle to the ribs.
In sand or mud between rocks, in the lower intertidal to shallow subtidal of open to semi-sheltered shores.
Looks a little like the cockle but is larger and more elongate.

White with yellowish-olive periostracum (skin). Grows to 6 cm long. Elongate oval, with a rounded anterior end and a more pointed posterior end. Thin-shelled and fragile, with the beak (apex) nearly in the centre of the dorsal edge. All bivalved molluscs have a flexible ligament, which along with the teeth, forms the hinge which holds the valves together. In Soletellina siliquens this ligament is very obvious and on the outside of the shell, just behind the beak.
Deposit feeder. The inhalant siphon reaches to the surface of the sand to suck in detritus and plankton. Spent water is expelled by the exhalant siphon.
Lives buried at about 8 cm below the surface in muddy sands in estuaries and harbours, intertidal to shallow subtidal.
The wafer shell is a close relative of the golden sunset shell, Soletellina nitida, but lives offshore from exposed beaches and the shell is more purple than white.
North Island. North Cape to Kapiti Island on the west coast and Hawke's Bay on the east coast. Widespread around the globe in subtropical and warm temperate seas.

Golden brown, up to 10 cm high. Large, solid, with thick spiral cords. Along the outer edge of the aperture there is a thickened ridge with nodules and there are brown and cream stripes on the inner edges of the aperture. The whole shell is covered in a thick hairy periostracum (skin).

Lays eggs in summer on harbour sand flats. The larva is in the plankton for almost 100 days, during which time it can be carried very long distances by currents. It settles inside a scallop which becomes a living larder until the juvenile Monoplex is just over 1cm long, after which it moves out to live independently.
Carnivorous. Preys on large bivalves, such as mussels and scallops.
In sheltered rocky areas, amongst brown seaweeds, at low tide down to at least 45 m water depth.
The animal is purplish grey with leopard spots.
White to yellowish-brown, with silky, yellowish olive periostracum (skin), grows up to 6 cm across, inflated, thin and fragile. Surface of the shell almost smooth.
Suspension feeder. Has long siphons that extend up to the surface of the mud.
Lives buried deep in soft mud in estuaries and tidal flats.
Fossil shells of Cyclomactra ovata (probably less than 10,000 years old) can be found in eroded layers in some estuaries such as the Tamaki estuary.
In New Zealand in various ports and harbours. An invasive species originally from China and Japan, but introduced to many places around the world.

Fairly small anemone with a olive-green to brown column with vertical orange, yellow, or pale stripes. The fine tentacles can range in colour from light grey-green to creamy brown or translucent ivory and usually number 25-50, but there may be as many as 100. Up to 30 mm high when open and expanded, and about 15 mm in diameter when contracted.

Reproduces asexually. It splits in half lengthwise to produce 2 individuals, but it can also pull away from its attachment and small individuals grow from the bits of tissue that are left behind. Also reproduces sexually, but probably only in its native range.
Carnivore. Uses the stinging cells on the tentacles to capture small planktonic prey.
On any hard substrate in the low intertidal to shallow subtidal, in harbours and estuaries and other sheltered areas.

Looks a little like the white-striped anemone, Anthothoe albocincta, which has alternating white and green stripes. Diadumene lineata has alternating orange and green stripes, and it has longer tentacles than Anthothoe.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Light yellowish to pinkish brown, up to 8 cm across. Shell large and heavy, almost circular, only slightly inflated. On the surface of the shell it has strong concentric ridges which divide in 2 and become almost frilled towards the dorsal edge.
Not much is known about the biology of the species, but the sexes are likely to be separate, they are thought to be broad-cast spawners with planktonic larvae. Can live for at least 26 years.
Buries itself in sand to a depth of up to 13 cm, in the low intertidal to about 10 m water depth, off exposed beaches. Usually only seen as washed up shells.
There are several species of Dosinia in New Zealand, but Dosinia anus is the largest and heaviest.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Carapace (body) pear-shaped with two spines at the front. Has long, hooked hairs on the body and legs to which it attaches bits of seaweed. Distinguished from other Notomithrax species by its relatively larger size and two small spines on the posterior edge of the carapace. The tips of the 'fingers' on the large claws are white.
Breeds from late July to end of March, larvae remain in the plankton for about 34 days.
Rocky shores, rock pools, amongst seaweed, also on sand or mud, intertidal to 50 m depth.
It is a slow mover and to avoid predators it usually covers itself in pieces of seaweed. It continuously changes these to match its background cover.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.
Whitish, grows to 10 cm long. Elongate, sculptured with concentric ridges which are crossed by radial ribs at the front end of the shells. There is a wide gap at the front when the shells are closed.

It is very common around Auckland, where it bores into the soft mudstone of tidal platforms. The ridges on the shell wear away the rock as the animal moves its shell. There is a third shelly plate that protects the ligament which holds the two larger shells together.
It has two long siphons which are fused together. It uses one siphon to draw in seawater from which it strains plankton. The second siphon expels the used seawater.
Bores into soft sandstone and mudstone of shore platforms.
Cosmopolitan, in New Zealand found along the east coast of the North Island as far south as the Bay of Plenty.

Light greenish to greyish brown, marbled with cream, with many scattered black spots and fewer and larger iridescent blue-green eye spots (ocelli) bordered by black. The animal is covered in seaweed-like papillae. It releases a purple dye when disturbed.

Lays long, tangled, green egg strings in late summer. When the eggs hatch the larval stage stays in the plankton for some time before it metamorphoses into a juvenile sea hare which has a shell. The shell is discarded when it grows to about 3mm. It takes about 3 months for it to grow to adult size.
Grazer. Feeds on cyanobacteria (which used to be called blue-green algae).
Low intertidal to 7 m depth, in sheltered harbours and estuaries.
Its seaweed-like camouflage is instantly disrupted by the cloud of dark violet dye it ejects when disturbed.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands.

Overall colour pinkish with concentric bands of reddish purple, pink and cream. Shell rather large, up to 6 cm long. Thin and elongate, with the beak (apex) near the centre of the top edge of the shell. Smooth and polished but with a sharpish fold which runs at an angle from the beak to the lower posterior edge.
Surface deposit feeder. Has a long inhalant siphon which reaches to the surface of the sand to suck in detritus and plankton. Spent water is expelled through the exhalant siphon.

Lives buried at a depth of about 20 cm in clean, fine- to -medium-grained sand in shallow water off protected and semi-protected beaches, usually found as beach-cast dead shells. From 0 - 140 m water depth, but most common shallower than 30 m depth.
Has concentric bands in various shades of reddish purple, pink or cream, elongate and thin.
North Island and northern South Island.

White with yellowish brown, up to 3.5 cm across. Shell rather small, inflated, circular in outline, but with a blunt beak (apex). Has closely-spaced, fine concentric lines on the surface of the shell.
Lives deeply buried in fine, soft mud which may be anoxic, in bays and on sheltered coasts, from shallow subtidal to 50 m water depth.
There are several species of Dosinia in New Zealand, but Dosinia lambata is the smallest and thinnest. The others are all much larger and thicker-shelled.

Not yet present in Auckland region, report any sightings to 0800 80 99 66 It has been found on several marine farms on Northland's east coast - at Houhora and Parengarenga harbours, as well as in Waikare Inlet, Orongo and Paroa Bays within the Bay of Islands. In the Bay of Islands it has also been reported from rocks near the entrance to the inlet at Waikino Creek, Okiato Point and Paihia.

White tubes, or ‘tunics’ which contain many small individual organisms and can sometimes appear orange flecked due to the bright orange colour of larvae within them. The long cylindrical tubes are generally between 5 - 30cm long, but in some instances up to 1.5m, and 5-20mm in diameter. Tubes are soft and pliable.

Eudistoma elongatum is an Australian sea squirt which forms large colonies or groups that attach to hard surfaces. It is not regarded as a serious nuisance to the aquaculture industry or the environment in its native Australia, but it may become so in New Zealand. It appears Eudistoma elongatum reduces in volume during the winter months, but once water temperatures lift it reappears in large volumes, usually over the summer.

Found on muddy-bottomed, tidal habitats, estuaries and sandy beaches, and on man-made structures such as wharf piles, mooring buoys and aquaculture equipment. It is generally submerged below the waterline, but can often be seen exposed at low tides.

Eudistoma looks like clusters of white or cream coloured tubes or 'sausages'. It was first reported in New Zealand in early 2005, but was not regarded as an issue at that time given its low density, lack of impacts overseas and the fact that it appeared to die off over winter. It has since spread through some areas of Northland. If you have seen Eudistoma outside of Northland, please take a photo and call MPI on 0800 80 99 66.

Males are a dark greyish brown, juveniles and females are a lighter, silvery brown. Pups are born black and will moult between two and three months of age. The flippers are rather short and narrow, the claws are barely noticeable. Males and females will grow up to 2.5 and 1.5 meters and weigh up to 180 and 50 kilograms respectively.

Males acquire and defend a territory which can include 5 to 8 females. Females give birth to a single pup between late November and December. Mothers stay with their young for 10 days before departing and beginning a cycle of feeding trips and pup attendance. They are sociable animals but should be left undisturbed if encountered.
Carnivorous, feeds on penguin, crab, fishes, squid and octopus. A foraging fur seal can dive down to 200 m for as long as 15 minutes.
Prefers rocky shores or boulder beaches for breeding. Can be spotted sun bathing on rocky shores or resting in sand dunes.
A stocky body and a long flat head, with a long pointed snout and a small pair of ears. The vibrissae (whiskers) are pale and long. The wet fur looks almost black.
Found around northern New Zealand. Indian, Pacific, and Atlantic Oceans under 40° latitude.

The body is dark smokey grey above and yellowish white below. Has forty to seventy throat pleats which extend to or past the navel. The dorsal fin is two thirds the way along the body. It rarely raises its fluke when diving. Males and females can reach 13.1 and 13.7 meters respectively.

It can exhale underwater and often does not produce a visible blow. It is usually seen alone or in pairs. Males and females are sexually mature past 11.5 meters in length. The gestation period is 12 months, lactation is for about 6 months. They can swim down to 300 meters and at speeds up to 25 km/hr.
Uses a number of methods, such skimming, gulp-feeding and bubble netting, to capture food which consists of plankton, crustaceans, and schooling fishes.
Inhabits waters warmer than 14° Celsius. Does not migrate so can breed anytime of the year. Females and calves have been observed in Hauraki Gulf all year round.
Is a baleen whale. It has a series of 3 longitudinal ridges on the head, the tip of the upper jaw is flat. The dorsal fin is deeply concave.
Coastal waters of the west coast of the North Island of New Zealand

The body has three well defined colours, grey, white, and black. The fins, the tip of the lower jaw, and the sides of the head are black. A black line runs over the head behind the blowhole. The ventral area is mostly white. Females grow up to 1.6 m and males to 1.45 m.

Lives in groups of 2 to 8 individuals but at times groups of up to 60 can be seen. Playful and acrobatic, it is known to follow boats, surf waves, and blow bubbles. The female gives birth to a single calf every 2 to 4 years. Can live up to 20 years. Rarely dives for more than a minute and a half.
Diet consists of bottom dwelling fish like sole, stargazer, and cod. It is also known to feed on squid, anchovies and crustaceans.
Lives within 8 km of shore in shallow (less than 75 m depth) and murky waters. This rare dolphin can be encountered anytime of the year as it does not leave its home range.
Has a chunky body and a conical head without a beak. The dorsal and pectoral fins are rounded like a Mickey Mouse ear.
Coastal and pelagic waters of the east and west coast of New Zealand.

Has a yellow thoracic (chest) patch and a light to medium grey patch on the flank. A dark stripe connects the flipper to the lower jaw and the eyes and the lips are surrounded by a dark patch. Males are larger than females and grow up to 2.7 m.

Can travel in groups of hundreds, sometimes thousands and can travel on average 50 km per day. The gestation period ranges between 9 and 11.5 months. Calves have been spotted in summer and winter months in the Hauraki Gulf, indicating it breeds all year in this region. Active and playful it is known to follow boats for hours and can put on great jumping shows.
Feeds on squid and schooling fishes like mackerel, anchovies and herring. Uses a few different hunting techniques, from high speed-pursuit to rounding up small schools of fishes, and fish whacking.
Found in all coastal waters around New Zealand. Has also been recorded from Tasmania, New Caledonia, the eastern and northwestern Atlantic and Pacific Oceans.
Has a unique and complex coloration. It is black above, white below, with a yellowish grey 8-shaped pattern on the sides.
Found around New Zealand. Occurs in all temperate waters of the southern hemisphere and in the northern Atlantic Ocean.

Can have various-sized white patches behind the dorsal fin and above the eye. An anchor-shaped whitish grey patch can be seen in front of the flippers and extending back to the genital area. The dorsal fin is low and rounded, situated closer to the head than the tail.

Very sociable, it forms groups of 10 to hundreds of individuals. Little is known about the biology of this mammal. Adult males can reach up to 6.7 meters and weigh up to 2.3 tonnes, a female can reach 5.7 meters and weigh up to 1.3 tonnes. Newborns are about 1.8 m and weigh around 75 kg. Males and females can live up to 45 and 60 years respectively.
Feeds mostly on squid and medium-sized fishes down to a depth of 500 m.
Pelagic, can been seen off shore on the east and west coast of New Zealand. Mass strandings of these animals often happen on New Zealand coasts.
Black and stocky with a very pronounced bulbous forehead but no beak. It is really a dolphin but behaves like a whale.
Can be encountered in all oceans of the globe, including throughout New Zealand.

Mostly black above and has well defined white patches above the eyes, on the belly (from the bottom jaw to the anus), and under the tail. It has a grey saddle patch behind the dorsal fin. The snout is pointed but does not have a beak. The pectoral fins are rounded. A male's dorsal fin can be as tall as 1.8 m, the female's 0.9 m.

Very sociable, it can form pods of up to 55 animals. Of the 3 to 5 types of orca, type A is the most commonly seen in New Zealand waters. Orca breed all year long, the gestation lasts for 15 to 18 months. Young will stay with the mother for up to two years. Sexual maturity is between 10 and 15 years old for females and 15 for males. Males and females can live up to 60 and 90 years old respectively.
Feeds on fishes and squid and has been observed to kill sharks. Known to attack seals, dolphins and large baleen whales. In New Zealand it is also known to target stingrays.
Pelagic and coastal, it can been seen on the east and west coasts of New Zealand.
A black body with sharply marked white patch above the eye. Dorsal fin can be very tall.
Can be encountered in all tropical and temperate waters of the globe, including throughout New Zealand.
The dorsal fin is large and hooked, placed halfway between the head and the tail. Males and females can grow up to 3.8 and 3.7 m respectively.

Very sociable, can form pods of up to 20 in coastal areas but up to a few hundred offshore. Breeds all year long and gestation lasts one year. Calves stay with their mothers for up to three years. Males and females can live up to 45 and 50 years of age respectively.

Feeds on a wide variety of prey. In shallow coastal waters will consume fishes and invertebrates that live on or near the bottom. Offshore it targets pelagic fishes and squid. Sometimes follows fishing boats and feeds on waste fish or fishes escaping from the nets.
Found around the globe in all tropical and temperate waters. Can be seen off shore and is frequently encountered in coastal waters of New Zealand all year round.

A robust, grey body with a short to medium-length beak. The superstar of dolphins, this species has featured in movies such as 'Flipper', 'The wild side', 'Dolphins of the Shadowland', 'The dolphins of Shark Bay', 'Beneath the blue', and 'Dolphin tale'.
This species can be encountered in all off shore tropical and temperate waters of the globe.

The body is robust and the head conical to square. It is grey above and white below. The dorsal fin is closer to the tail than the head. It can reach a maximum length of 3.8 m and weight up to 450 kg. Females grow larger than males. These whales have teeth only on the bottom jaw.

Forms pods of up to 6 individuals. It has an ink sac near the anus which is filled with up to 12 litres of brown liquid. It is released when the whale is distressed - just like in squid. The gestation period lasts about a year, and it can live for up to 23 years.
Feeds on squid, fish and crustaceans.
Occurs in all tropical and temperate waters of the globe, and can be seen off shore on the east or west coasts of New Zealand if the sea surface is calm enough.

A small, extremely rare whale, which is almost never seen alive. It often lies motionless just beneath the surface. Has a small curved dorsal fin and narrow underslung lower jaw. A white patch between eye and fin looks like a gill. It almost looks like a shark.
Can be encountered in all oceans of the globe, including around New Zealand, down to 50° latitude.

Dark grey all over, with white lips. The dorsal fin is short and rounded, situated closer to the tail. A series of humps follows the dorsal ridge between the dorsal fin and the tail. The lower jaw is narrow and armed with large teeth which fit into sockets in the upper jaw. A male will reach a 18.3 m length and a female 12 m.

Of all marine mammals it can dive the deepest, to 3,200 m, and for the longest, up to two hours. It can swim as fast as 12 knots. Large males are often by themselves but groups of 20 to 30 animals can occur. A female will give birth every 4 to 6 years. Can live up to 70 years old.
Feeds mainly on medium to large size squid. A 12 m giant squid weighing 200 kg has been found in a stranded whale's stomach. Also feeds on deep-sea fishes.
Occurs from the equator to the poles. It favours continental slopes and submarine canyons. Can be seen close to shore where deep water meets land, for example around Kaikoura in the South Island.
A large whale with a disproportionately large head. The blowhole, at the front left-hand-side of the head, gives it a uniquely angled blow. The skin between the head and the tail is wrinkled.
Found only in theSouthern Hemisphere between 30° and 45 ° latitude.

Mostly a dark greyish brown. In juveniles the beak may be darker, but in adults the beak, together with much of the forehead, is white. Can have white patches around the genitals. It has small teeth on the upper jaw and only males have an exposed pair of triangular shaped teeth rising from the lower jaw. Males and females can grow up to 5.7 and 5.3 m respectively.
Usually seen singly or in pairs. On rare occasions it has been recorded in pods of up to 28 individuals. Nothing is known of its biology.
It is thought to feed on deep-sea squid.
Occurs off shore. Animals seen close to shore are usually injured or dying.
A slender whale with a long narrow beak. Lifts its long beak out of the water when surfacing.
North Island, South Island down to Fiordland and Otago, Stewart Island.

Dark green. Prostrate and corrugated, forming lobed cushions 2 - 3 cm thick and up to 20 cm or more across. Attached to rock by a mass of spongy filaments. First described in 1932 from a specimen from Motutapu, Waitemata Harbour.
Little is known about the biology of this species.
Lower intertidal in fairly sheltered locations. Found on shaded rocks.
Alga with a velvety texture. Forms a low clinging cushion.
Throughout New Zealand and overseas locations including Australia and Argentina.
Up to 30 cm or more high. Branched, stems are round in cross-section. Texture firm and velvety. Hairs conspicuous. Attached by a holdfast made up of an expanded disc.
Most Codium species have male and female gametangia on separate plants. Gametangia are the cells which produce gametes (egg or sperm cells).
Low intertidal to subtidal. Found on open coasts on rocky surfaces.
Robust, branched, velvety, dark green alga.
East and west coasts of the North Atlantic, northern Africa, South Africa, South Australia, Victoria and New Zealand.
Large green alga with spongy branches that always divide into 2. Velvety texture. Grows to between 15 and 60 cm, but can reach 1m. Is shorter on high energy coasts where waves break off branches.
Dies back in autumn/winter, but can regenerate each spring from the perennial holdfast.
Needs hard surfaces to grow on. Can survive a wide range of temperature and salt concentrations, found from estuaries to fully marine, intertidal to 15m water depth.
Invasive species, first noticed in Auckland Harbour in 1973. Has since spread further along many coasts.
Begins with a single central stalk and then branches, but each branch always divides dichotomously, which means that they always divide into 2.
North, South, Stewart and Auckland Islands. Elsewhere in Australia, Europe and North America, parts of Africa and Asia.

Grass-green or yellowish green. Up to 20 cm high, tubular, unbranched, tips rounded. Has a soft texture and the plant tears easily. May be filled with gas bubbles and if it comes away from the substrate it will rise to the top and continue to grow.
Alternates between a gametophyte which is the plant stage that produces gametes (egg or sperm cells) and a sporophyte which is the plant stage that produces spores.

Common in rocks in pools, especially those in the upper intertidal zone. Often grows on shells and other plants. Does not mind stagnant water and is very tolerant of a wide range of salt concentrations. Does well in areas of high pollution.
Irregular grass-green tubes that grow from a narrow disc-shaped base. The tubes look a bit like intestines which gives them both the common and scientific names.
Throughout New Zealand. Native to the Indo-Pacific region, but invasive in Europe, North America, east Africa and eastern Asia.

Bright green. Grows in thin but tough sheets which are up to 20 cm long but only 2 cells thick. Changes from rounded shape to irregularly lobed as it grows. Has circular wrinkles near the holdfast (attachment).
At the reproductive stage the sheets develop a wide yellow-green band along the edge. Once the spores are released only the cell walls remain, giving the plants a tattered look.
Lower to upper intertidal zone in a wide variety of habitats. Does especially well when both light and nutrient levels are high.
Grows in sheets that look a little like lettuce and which can be eaten. Early Māori cooked sea lettuce and today it is still eaten by many around the world.
Through out New Zealand, also Australia.
Up to 30 cm high. When young it is fan shaped, but becomes divided as it ages into narrow segments. Texture is firm and it is quite tough when mature.
Attached to rock by a holdfast that is a truncated disc.
From lower intertidal to 5m. Found on open coasts, also occurs in rock pools.
Upright and branched into narrow segments with narrow tips or broadly fan-shaped when young. Brown with golden tips or greenish.
A fine mesh of interlinked branches forms spongy green cushions, often more than 10 cm across.
The cellulose of the cells walls have a crystalline structure and the plant therefore takes a long time to break down after death.
Intertidal rock platforms, prefers shaded spots protected from surf or surge.
Forms spongy cushions which are bright green when wet and grey-brown when dry.
Australasian. In New Zealand, Three Kings Islands, North Island and northern South Island, including northwest Nelson and Pelorus Sound.

Dark green and glossy. Usually around 10 cm high, but can get to 20 cm high in deeper water. Swollen bladders are found on all sides of the upright stems, but in deeper water they are found in opposite pairs. The holdfast (attachment) consists of smooth, glassy stolons ('runners') which are attached by rhizoids (hair-like structures). It has a crisp texture.
Likes rocky, open coasts, where it is found from the low intertidal to subtidal.
Has lots of swollen glossy green bladders along a central stem.
Australasian. In New Zealand, Three Kings Islands, North Island and northern South Island, including Marlborough Sounds.

Bright green, robust plants up to 40 cm high. With fern-like fronds. The frond branchlets end in 1-2 sharp, colourless points and the fronds grow from tangled, coarse runners which are covered by sharp spines and which are attached by rhizoids (hair-like structures).
On rocks and gravel on open coasts from the subtidal to deep water.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands, Australia, Norfolk and Lord Howe Islands.

Up to 50 cm high. Branching. The size of the hollow beads will vary according to habitat, but they are often about 1 cm diameter. The holdfast is a fleshy disc. Colour ranges from dull ochre to greenish or grey brown.
Each plant is either male or female. Plants are regularly exposed during low tides. Genus only found in Australasia, Norfolk and Lord Howe Islands.
Intertidal, attached to rock, or attached to stones in regions of soft sediment. Occurs on moderately exposed reefs as well as in sheltered calm locations.
Branching seaweed, with each branch consisting of a chain of hollow beads.

Originally from Japan but invasive around the world. First discovered In New Zealand in Wellington Harbour in 1987 and now found from Auckland to Stewart Island in almost all international ports and harbours, also the Snares, Fiordland and Chatham Islands. Spreads slowly naturally, but is easily spread on boat hulls and marine gear.

Golden-brown to green-brown. Can grow to 2 m tall. Once the plants are over 5 cm tall they have a very obvious midrib. Young plants are broadly oval in shape but leaf edges become more lobed as the plants grow. The holdfast (attachment) consists of a tangle of slim, branched haptera (root-like structures).

As for many seaweeds it has two life stages with different appearances. It has a microscopic gametophyte which produces gametes (egg or sperm cells) from separate male and female plants. This stage is so small it goes mostly unnoticed. The large seaweed stage is the sporophyte which lasts about 6 months before dying back and which produces spores.

Grows on any hard surface including rocks, shells, boats, wharf piles, from the low intertidal to 15 m depth. It can form dense forests in sheltered areas, as well as growing on the open coast under Durvillaea and amongst Carpophyllum and with Macrocystis.

Golden-brown, with oval lobed blades which look a little like the native Ecklonia kelp, but which have a very obvious midrib once plants are over 5 cm. Native to China, Japan and Korea where it is cultured and eaten.
Through out New Zealand, also west coast South America.

Up to 50 cm high. Golden brown when young, dark brown when mature. The forked thalli (leaves) may be up to 2 cm wide. Has a firm texture, but young plants are floppy. Older plants can look shaggy when they become covered with ligulae. These are tear-shaped structures that house the spore capsules. Attached to hard substrate by a fairly small holdfast of short, slender root-like haptera.
Dictyota grows through the repeated division of a single cell at the tip of each thallus (leaf).
Found on open coasts. From low spring tide to deeper water.
Upright, flat ribbon-like thalli (leaves) fork repeatedly into 2 with tongue-like outgrowths along the strap-like branches.
Through out New Zealand. Widespread arund the world.
2-5 cm high, and up to 10 cm across. Young plants are golden yellow, smooth and rounded, but become darker, eroded and unevenly lobed with age. Surface gummy, but the texture is crisp.
From sheltered to moderately exposed locations. High to low intertidal. On rocky substrate or as epiphyte on other seaweeds, particularly coralline algae.
A yellow, encrusting alga, which forms hollow bubbled cushions.
Has a south circumpolar distribution, including the southern South American coast. Throughout New Zealand and offshore islands, but more common in the south.

Brown to golden brown. May grow as long as 10 m, although usually 3-5 m long. The holdfast (attachment) is an irregular broad cone from which the solid, cylindrical stipe (stem) grows. The stipe widens out into a broad, flattened blade that divides into the characteristic long straps. The number of straps are greatest on more exposed coasts and as many as 100 per plant have been counted. The straps float because they are not solid but instead have an airfilled internal honeycomb structure.
Durvillaea antarctica reproduces sexually by producing egg and sperm that are released into the water, usually in winter. A large plant may release as many as 100 million eggs in one night.
Attached to rock at and just below low water mark, particularly on exposed coast.
Has very long brown, flattened, rubbery strap-like blades. In some countries it is harvested for alginates, which have many industrial uses, and as food in South America.
North Island and South Island down to Banks Peninsula and Milford Sound.

Up to 1.5 m. The main stem, side branches and leaves are all flattened, and the main stem and sidebranches have a somewhat zigzag outline. The side branches and leaves alternate and where the leaves join there is often a bladder with a pointed tip. Has a strong, tangled holdfast (attachment) which allows it to cope with strong wave surge.

Flapjack is long-lived and slow-growing, but it grows faster and bigger in dense stands. Carpophyllum has a direct life history, producing egg and sperm. It does not have any alternative life history stage.
Found on rocky substrate in the low intertidal and below, where it forms a distinct zone. On open coasts, in channels and rock pools, but does not like sand-scour.

Olive brown, long and leathery. The side branches alternate along the main stem. In the joints where the leaves meet the stem there are reproductive structures. These are responsible for the plant's first name of Carpophyllum, with carpo meaning fruit, and phyllum meaning leaf.
North, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Also southern Australia.
Golden brown. Up to 1 m high, main stem robust and zigzagged. Side branches alternate and have tight clusters of smooth, swollen, fingers. Firm and crisp.

Cystophora torulosa is one of the brown seaweeds that contain phlorotannins. These compounds are found in the cell walls of the plant and are thought to play a number of roles. Amongst others, they may protect the plant from UV light damage, as well as defend it from grazing by herbivores.
On rocks in the lower intertidal down to 3 m water depth, on moderately exposed coasts, and in pools and channels.
Has short, swollen side branches that come off a zigzag main stem.
Throughout New Zealand, except Chatham Islands. Australia, southern Africa, parts of west African coast.

Golden brown, can grow to over 1 m long. It has a long, cylindrical stipe (stem) which expands into a flattened central blade. The margins of the blade divide into a number of long, broad, flattened fronds that lie in the same plane as the blade. Frond surfaces vary from smooth to corrugated (pictured), and frond margins vary from serrated to extremely spiny. The holdfast (attachment) consists of sturdy haptera (root-like structures) that divide repeatedly to form a broad cone which anchors the plant firmly to any hard substrate.
Kelp plants produce spores and these can grow into minute plants that produce eggs and sperm. Once an egg is fertilised it grows into the large leafy kelp stage.
Attached to rock at and below low water (spring tide) to deep water on exposed to reasonably sheltered coasts.
A large golden brown kelp with a single cylindrical stipe (stem) and a number of large, flattened fronds that come off a large central flat blade.
North, South, Steward and Chatham Islands. Also Chile, Tristan da Cunha, southern Africa and southern Australia.

Green-brown to pale yellow at the tips, older plants are dark brown. Usually less than 20 cm high. Swollen stem with many side branches that are narrower at point of origin and rounded at the tips. The whole plant is filled with clear, thick mucilage (a gluey mixture of proteins and sugars). Stiff and firm, becoming leathery with age.
An annual species, which dies back after summer.
Attached to intertidal rocks on moderately exposed coast.

Swollen central stem with cylindrical branches that are pinched at the point where they join the main stem. Filled with mucilage, which is a gluey mixture of proteins and sugars that, amongst other things, helps the plant store water and food.
Northern North Island and Three Kings Islands. Also southern Australia including Tasmania.
50 cm or more high, flattened stems dividing dichotomously (dividing in two), creating many-branched fans. The holdfast (attachment) is a flanged and divided extension of the stem.

Xiphophora chondrophylla produces both eggs and sperm on the same plant. They are produced on the upper branches which get a warty look when they are fertile. Plants contain a lot of mucilage (a gluey mixture of proteins and sugars).
Low intertidal to 20 m, but most common at the low tide level. On exposed coasts.
Greyish brown alga with flattened stems that divide repeatedly in two with the dividing branches slightly in-curved, creating a more or less tear-drop shaped space between the branches.
Through out New Zealand, including the Kermadec Islands. Also widely distributed overseas.

Grows up to 4 cm high but frequently shorter. Although the colour is generally dull pink, it can be bleached and tinged with green. Branches pinnately arranged (feather-like) and made up of calcified segments. Rather flattened at the branch tips. Holdfast is a small calcified plate. First described from a European specimen.
Part of a worldwide genus. May grow in clumps, as a turf, or as a bright pink paint on the surface of rocks.
Intertidal, and forms turf in sheltered reef environments.
Short, erect, dull pink branching alga that is stiff and brittle.
Cosmopolitan. In New Zealand, Kermadec, Three Kings and North Islands, northern South Island extending down to Fiordland on the west coast.

Dark crimson, or dark purplish-red, bleaching to greenish brown. Plants up to 20 cm high, occur in dense growths. Stems flattened, the central stem has narrow branches which may or may not come off opposite each other. The base of the stem is often without branches and branches get progressively shorter further up the stem giving it a 'Christmas tree' look. Texture is firm to wiry.
Plants reproduce by tetraspores and sexually reproducing plants (which produce eggs and spermatia).
Usually found in large pools and channels in the intertidal where water remains at low tide, not common.
Dark red with flattened fronds which often have a 'Christmas-tree' shape.
Northern North Island, down to Tolaga Bay on the east coast and Raglan on the west coast.

Greenish to nearly black. Up to 13 cm high, usually 5-7 cm. Dichotomously branched (which means the branches always divide in two), bushy-looking plants. Towards the curled tips the branches become flattened and develop a channel. The holdfast (attachment) is a small, fleshy disc. Plants have a cartilaginous texture.
In some red algae, such as Psilophycus alveatus, plants develop cystocarps which produce carpospores. These develop into a plant that looks similar to the original parent plant.
On mid-intertidal rocks on open sand beaches of the northern North Island where it forms a distinctive black zone above low water.

Greenish to nearly black, especially when dry. Often has curled tips to the branches and a bushy appearance and makes a distinct zone in the intertidal. First described from a specimen collected on Cook’s first voyage, 1769-1770, from either Mercury Bay or the Bay of Islands.
Restricted to the North Island and northern offshore islands.

Olive green to brown-purple or dull crimson. Erect plant up to 60 cm. Very variable in shape, but starts with a definite stem which is round in cross-section. The thalli (leaves) can be broad or narrow, undivided or forked fronds. A characteristic feature of the species is that the edges of the leave are often divided and pointed or irregularly split or torn. The holdfast (attachment) is an expanded disc. Firm to cartilaginous in texture.
Recent DNA studies have shown that Pachymenia lusoria only occurs in the North Island and that plants south of Cook Strait are a different species.
Low intertidal rocky surfaces on exposed coasts, where it forms a distinct zone often as the only algal species there.

Very variable in the shape of its thalli (leaves), but always starts with an elongate stipe (stem) which is round in cross-section, after which the many leaves can be broad or slender, unbranched or forked.
New Zealand and Campbell Island. Branched plants only found from Northland to Coromandel Peninsula and in the northern South Island at Nelson.

Brick red to dull crimson when wet, and black when dry. Under 2 cm high. Grows as a flat crust or as a crust with short branches with rounded knobbly ends. The knobbed branches are cylindrical, forked and tightly packed into rounded tufts. The holdfast (attachment) is the lower surface of the crust.

Has pit-like conceptacles, which are the cavities that house the reproductive organs. The fungus Mycosphaerella apophlaea is often found in the walls and conceptacles of Apophlaea sinclairii, but it is not known for certain whether the association is symbiotic.
Forms flat or knobbly dark red or blackish leathery crusts on rocks in the upper intertidal.
North Island , northern South Island, Chatham Islands.

A characteristic feature of this plant is its iridescence. Old growths are light green, but younger growth is a mixture of brilliant iridescent green, blue or purple flecks. Small, up to 3 cm high, can be either upright or prostrate, branches consist of fat segments that are tapered at either end and which form tangled layers. The holdfast (attachment) is a small disc.
Likes to grow on the bases of other seaweeds, but it will also make new attachments where horizontal branches touch the substrate. When fronds break they exude a gummy carbohydrate.
Found at or near the low tide mark around the margins of shallow pools. It will also attach to fragments of shell, sand, or rock. It appears to prefer shallow pools or channels with moving water.
Small plants with short, fat tangled branches which are a vivid iridescent purple-blue underwater.
North, South and Chatham Islands. Also southern Australia.

Small brown to dark brown, makes stoloniferous (made of creepers) tangled mats 20-30 cm wide and 1-5 mm thick. The mats are so tangled that it is difficult to recognise individual plants. Fronds are usually brown to dark red-brown towards the outside of the mats, but may be greenish yellow inside. It may cover large areas on flat shore platforms.

In the mid intertidal on rocks in sheltered and moderately exposed sites, but found higher up the shore on more exposed coasts or in shaded places. Also an epiphyte on mangrove pneumatophores (airbreathing roots), mussels or limpets.
Small, fine plants which form a dark-coloured tangled mat.
Kermadec Islands and northern New Zealand to Cook Strait. Also southern Australia.

Pale pink, the tips are a darker red and the lower stems are coated in a thin white chalk. A bushy plant that is flexible despite the chalk coating. Up to 7 cm high. The branches are cylindrical and divide dichotomously (dividing in two) and they become slightly thinner after each division. The holdfast (attachment) is an expanded disc.
Develops reproductive bodies called cystocarps. These develop after fertilization and produce carpospores. The carpospores grow into a plant that looks similar to the original parent plant.
Common in intertidal pools and shallow water where it grows on rock, and very occasionally as an epiphyte in deeper water.

Small and bushy, mainly pale pink to white. Liagora harveyana is the only mainland New Zealand species of Liagora, but other species are found in the Kermadec Islands and further north as most species of Liagora prefer warmer waters.
Three Kings Islands, North Island, northern South Island. Also south eastern Australia.

Dark red when wet, drying to black. Grows to at least 20 cm high and grows in dense, stiff and wiry tufts. The lower stems are cylindrical and become flattened further up. Fronds divide dichotomously (divide in two) forming fans of narrow branches. The branch tips are slightly lighter in colour, slightly thicker and have rounded tips. The holdfast (attachment) is an expanded pad.

Develops reproductive bodies called a cystocarps, which cluster near the tips of the branches. These develop after fertilization and produce carpospores which grow into a plant that looks similar to the original parent plant.
On rock at or below low spring tide on exposed coasts.
Dark red when wet and black when dry, grows in dense fan-shaped tufts.
North, South and Chatham Islands. Also Africa and Australia.
Loose to dense clumps of tough blue-green spiky stems (which are modified leaves), with dark brown spreading flower or seed heads near the tips of some stems.
Flowers from September to December, has seed from November to April. Produces seeds but also makes new plants through rhizomes (underground shoots).
Salt marshes, estuaries, brackish streams and lagoons, as well as inland around geothermal vents.
Grows in brackish, muddy places such as by mangroves. Has spreading seed heads near the ends of long pale blue-green stems. Used by Māori as outer thatch for houses.
North, South and Stewart Islands. Also Australia and Papua New Guinea.
Grass-like with long, narrow, flat leaves attched to short branches which in turn are attached to creeping rhizomes (underground shoots). Forms dense seagrass beds.

Flowers from October to February, has seed from January to February. Has wide salinity tolerance, but narrow temperature tolerance. Also does not cope well with large amounts of silt and poor water quality.
On sheltered intertidal and subtidal sand and mudflats down to 6 m water depth.
Has long, bright to mid-green grass-like blades attached to short stems. Seagrass beds are important habitat and nursery grounds for many marine species.
North Island to Kawhia on the west coast and Ohiwa Harbour on the east coast. Also eastern Australia and Lord Howe Island.

In northern New Zealand grows to 5-6 m high, but gets smaller the further south it grows. Salt-tolerant, it excretes salt through the leaves which are shiny on the upper surface and covered by a dense white felt underneath. Creates a shallow raft of roots which may be many times wider than the diameter of the tree's canopy. Its many pneumatophores (air-breathing roots) allow it grow in anaerobic muds which have little oxygen.

Flowers from February to April. Propagules (partially developed seeds) appear from December to January. The propagule usually has the first set of roots and leaves partially developed before it falls off the tree.
Colonist of muds and silts in northern estuaries and harbours. Prefers sheltered conditions. Not frost tolerant when young.
A small tree in the north, dwindling to a small shrub in the south of its range. Creates a broad, shallow raft of roots which produce the characteristic pneumatophores (air-breathing roots).
New Zealand and offshore islands. Widespread in southern hemisphere.

Forms a clump of radiating, stiff, green and orange-brown spiky stems (which are modified leaves), which can grow to 1 m high. The inflorescence (flower cluster) is dark brown and knobbly and found a few centimetres below the tip of the spiky stem.
Produces tiny nut-like seeds, but also makes new plants through rhizomes (underground shoots).
Has red-brown knobbly 'flower heads' near the top of the spiky green and orange-brown stalks.
North Island, northern South Island, Chatham Islands. Records further south are questionable.

Purple or red brown, bleaching to pink or cream, up to 50 cm high. Has large leafy blades which are irregular and ragged in shape, and which in older plants have a warty texture. The holdfast (attachment) is a small expanded disc.

The tetrasporangial sori (patches where tetraspores are produced) are scattered all over the surface of the leaf in older plants. In female gametophytes the cystocarps are scattered over the blades giving a warty texture. Sarcothalia atropurpurea is being investigated as a candidate for aquaculture because it contains high quality carrageenan which is used by the food industry as a gelling and thickening agent.
On rocks and in pools in the lower intertidal, on open coasts.
Large, irregular blades which are a rich red brown when wet, but bleach to pink or cream in bright sunlight.
North Island and northern South island, but more common in the north. Also Lord Howe Island.

Dark purply brown to olive green, up to 12 cm high, but usually shorter. Branches divide dichotomously (divide in two), and are flattened and fleshy, with many short branchlets along the edges, especially in female plants. In spore-bearing plants the branches are much more cylindrical.
Female plants develop stalked, globular cystocarps. These are reproductive bodies which develop after fertilization and produce carpospores.
On intertidal and subtidal rocks on moderately exposed coasts.
Olive green to reddy brown, with flattened central stems which have a large number of short branchlets along the margins.
Purply brown to olive green, up to 17 cm high. Starts with a cylindrical stem which forks near the base. Each fork fans out into a flattened, fleshy blade that is fringed by numerous thin rods.

Has lobed cystocarps (reproductive bodies which develop on the female plant after fertilisation) along the edges of the blade. Also has lighter coloured zones of spermatangia (which produce spermatia) on the lobes of the blades.
Low intertidal, on rocks in the surf zone.
Forked flattened blades fringed by numerous thin branchlets.
Northern North Island, east coast to Auckland.

Golden brown to olive green, can get to 1 m high. At first the plant has low growing, spotted leaves (pictured) that are about 5 cm long, narrow and have a midrib. The edges are toothed. Then the plant grows a long stem which is also toothed and the leaves are still spotted but longer and narrower.
Sargassum scabridum belongs to a genus that is distributed widely around the world.
On rocks in low intertidal to subtidal pools.
Has different leaves depending on the growth stage.
Southern distribution, including New Zealand, southern Australia and east coast of South America.

Purply black to grey-brown. Bushy plant which can grow to over 30 cm high. Clumps of slender cylindrical stems, which may be branched or unbranched, come off a small cartilaginous holdfast (attachment). Soft and pliable. In muddy areas or where there is a flow of fresh water plants are often smaller.

Males and females are separate plants. Cystocarps (on female gametophytes) are often in beaded rows on the thin branches and the spermatangia (male reproductive cells that produce the spermatia) are in sunken pits scattered over the fronds.
On boulders, rocks, or sand, but appears to need sheltered environments, intertidal to 12 m depth.
Large, purply black bushy plants with untidy thin branches.
Auckland Harbour, Taranaki, Hawkes Bay, southern Wairarapa, South, Stewart and Chatham Islands. Also widespread in Europe and the Americas.

Olive brown when wet, but darker when dry. Has narrow, wiry branches that divide irregularly but always dichotomously (always divide in two). The branches are covered in whorls of small filaments which make them look a little like the branchlets on rimu trees.
On intertidal and shallow subtidal rocks affected by sediment.
Has narrow, wiry stems that look a little like the branchlets on a rimu tree.
Northern New Zealand to Cook Strait, Three Kings and Chatham Islands.

Golden to greenish brown and up to 1 m high but usually shorter. The leaves along the fringes of the main stem are variable in shape, ranging from narrow to broad, and from relatively simple to lobed (pictured). In the joint where the fringing leaf meets the stem there are reproductive structures, called receptacles, on long stalks. These are specialised structures that contain the conceptacles or reproductive organs.

Like its close flapjack relative, Carpophyllum plumosum produces eggs and sperm. In Carpophyllum once the egg is fertilised it drops to the rock below where it immediately starts to grow into another large leafy stage.
On rocks in pools and channels in moderate shelter on exposed coasts, from low intertidal into subtidal.
Has a flattened main stem which has a fringe of smaller leaves that are often lobed like oak leaves. These leaves are also flattened and lie in the same plane as the main stem.
A perennial grass. The tough, blue-green leaves grow in tight bundles from creeping stolons (runners) which may be metres long. Salt and wind tolerant.

Male and female flowers are on separate plants. Flowers appear from September to December and the female plant produces the characteristic 'tumbleweed' seed heads from November to May. These break off and are dispersed by the wind. When they are buried the seeds germinate to produce new plants.
Active coastal dunes and sands. Often grows with pingao.

Coloniser of dune areas. Binds sand and so is considered an important stabiliser. However, it prefers active dune areas and does not do well in stable dunes as it is outcompeted by introduced dune plants.
Tough leaves, which are yellow-green when young, and orange-gold when dry. The leaves grow in closely spaced bundles along the very long, stout and much-branched creeping stolons (runners).
Is wind-pollinated. Flowers from spring to early summer and the seed appears in late summer.
Coastal sand dunes, prefers the fronts of active dunes. Often grows with spinifex. Under pressure from harvesting, trampling, vehicles, browsing animals and competition by marram grass.

Coloniser of dune areas and good at trapping sand. Prefers to grow in active dune areas, but is vulnerable to competition from introduced species such as marram grass. Highly prized by Māori weavers for its gold colour and used in tukutuku panels, as well as kete (bags) and other woven items.

Alderman, Stanley, Red Mercury, Cuvier, Hen and Chicken, Little and Great Barrier Islands. Tiritiri Matangi Island in Hauraki Gulf is the only place around Auckland where tuatara are frequently seen (at night).

The colour varies from olive green to brown to orange. Has a row of white spines along its back. Males can grow up to 61 cm long. Males can weigh up to 1.3 kg and females up to 0.5 kg. Slow moving, which make them vulnerable to predation. It is nocturnal.

Sheds the skin once a year and can live up to a 100 years. Both sexes become sexually mature between 15 and 20 years old. A female tuatara can lay and bury up to 12 eggs every four years. Eggs take 12 to 16 months to hatch. Eggs incubated at 22 degrees Centigrade produce mostly male tuatara, eggs incubated at 20 degrees produce mostly females.
Carnivorous. Feeds on insects, lizards, sea bird eggs and chicks.
Lives in forests, grassland, and along the sea shore where it can be found sleeping in bird burrows.

Neither a dinosaur nor a lizard, tuatara is a cold blooded reptile. Sometimes called a living fossil, it is the only surviving member of the order Sphenodontia which goes back to the age of the dinosaurs.
Eastern Pacific Ocean and western Indian Ocean. Occasionally in New Zealand coastal waters.
Has a maximum of 40 dark rings. The dorsal coloration is otherwise beige to orange, snout and lips are yellow. Females grow larger than males, up to 1.6 m.

Goes onto land to moult, lay eggs, and digest prey. In the tropics it is often found ashore resting in vegetation, leaf litter, trees, and in underground bird nests. It is very poisonous but also very shy and will avoid danger. It can dive down to depths of 60 m. Oviparous (lays eggs), the female can lay 4 to 20 eggs during the summer months.

Is comfortable underwater, on dry land, or in trees. It could just as easily be a terrestrial snake which spends some of its time underwater. Encountered mostly in the tropics, sometimes specimens have drifted down to New Zealand, probably with warm summer currents.
Has a distinctively dark and pale-ringed body, and yellow lips. The tail is compressed sideways to form a paddle.

Can weigh up to 200 kg, with the carapace (shell) up to 124 cm long. The carapace and scales are a uniform reddish-brown colour, the skin is creamy white to yellowish brown. The carapace is often covered by a thin layer of green algae and barnacles.

These turtles nest over a great geographic range from tropical to temperate seas. Nesting is in spring and early summer. Females come to shore at night to dig a nest in sand above the high tide mark where they lay between 64 and 200 eggs. Females will lay one to seven times a year every two to three years. Temperature in the nest controls the hatching period (45 to 80 days) and the sex of newborns (32° C and above develop into females, 28° C and under into males).
Omnivorous, feeds on crustaceans, bivalves, jellyfish, fishes, sponges and seaweeds.
Occasionally visits New Zealand coasts. Has been found out at sea, in bays, lagoons and river mouths. Can dive down to 233 m and stay underwater for up to an hour.
Has a large head with a parrot-like beak. Flippers are armed with two claws.
North half of the North Island of New Zealand but once recorded off Banks Peninsula.
Can weigh up to 182 kg. The carapace (shell) can be up to 120 cm long. The carapace and scales are brown, the underside is white to pale yellow.

The females nest in 2 or 3 year cycles at which time they will lay between one and seven clutches of eggs. Females come to shore at night to dig a nest in sand above the high tide mark and to lay, on average, 110 eggs. Temperature in the nest controls the hatching period and the sex of new-borns. A green turtle will mature very late, between 30 and 40 years old and die around 59 years of age
Herbivorous, feeds mostly on seaweed and sea grass.
A tropical turtle, occasionally visits northern New Zealand. Can dive to 110 m and can stay underwater for up to 66 minutes
The carapace is domed, smooth, and wide. Has a small rounded head and a single claw on each flipper.
North half of the North Island of New Zealand but once recorded off Palliser Bay.
Can weigh up to 80 kg and the oval carapace (shell) can reach 90 cm long. The shell is an amber brown with black markings. The underside is light yellow to white.

The female lays about 130 eggs every three years. Females come to shore at night to dig a nest in the sand above the high tide mark in which they lay the eggs. A nest temperature above 30.3 will produce only females. They spend the first one to three years of their life at sea before moving into reefs and bays.
Omnivorous, feeds on invertebrates and are known to consume sponges.
A tropical turtle, occasionally visits northern New Zealand. Can dive to 100 m and can stay underwater for up to 74 minutes
The head is narrow and pointed. The carapace is oval with strongly serrated posterior margins. Has two claws on each flipper.
